// ── 365 scriptures by month/day ───────────────────────────────────────────────
// Themes: Jan=New Beginnings, Feb=Identity, Mar=Renewal, Apr=Hope,
//         May=Strength, Jun=Endurance, Jul=Freedom, Aug=Body as Temple,
//         Sep=Discipline, Oct=Gratitude, Nov=Rest, Dec=Light & Reflection

const BY_MONTH = {
  1: [
    { v:"This means that anyone who belongs to Christ has become a new person. The old life is gone; a new life has begun!", r:"2 Corinthians 5:17", d:"You are not a patched-up version of who you were. In Christ, the old identity built on performance, comparison, and shame is actually gone. This isn't a pep talk; it's a declaration of reality. The question isn't whether God has made you new. The question is whether you'll live from that newness today — in the gym, in your relationships, in the quiet choices no one sees. New person. New standard. Show up as that." },
    { v:"For I am about to do something new. See, I have already begun! Do you not see it?", r:"Isaiah 43:19", d:"God says 'I have already begun' — present tense, right now. The new thing rarely looks dramatic at first. It starts as a decision to show up when you'd rather not, a small shift in priorities, a flicker of discipline where there used to be only comfort. Don't dismiss what's growing in you because it's not impressive yet. Pay attention. The God who spoke galaxies into existence is doing something in you right now." },
    { v:"The faithful love of the Lord never ends! His mercies never cease. Great is his faithfulness; his mercies begin afresh each morning.", r:"Lamentations 3:22–23", d:"Lamentations was written in catastrophe — the city destroyed, the people scattered. And in that rubble the author found something that didn't require good circumstances: mercies, new every morning. Not earned. Not conditional on yesterday's performance. Just new, every single day. Whatever you're carrying from yesterday — the failure, the missed rep, the conversation you wish went differently — it doesn't follow you into today. New mercy is already here." },
    { v:"For I know the plans I have for you, says the Lord. They are plans for good and not for disaster, to give you a future and a hope.", r:"Jeremiah 29:11", d:"This promise wasn't given to people in comfort — it was given to exiles who had lost everything. The future and hope God promises don't require you to have it figured out. They require trusting the One who does. Your training, your career, your relationships — God's plans for your good are already in motion, even in the seasons that don't look like it yet." },
    { v:"I focus on this one thing: forgetting the past and looking forward to what lies ahead.", r:"Philippians 3:13", d:"Paul wrote this from prison. The man who said 'forgetting what is behind' had more behind him than most of us ever will — both victories and catastrophic failures. Forgetting doesn't mean pretending the past didn't happen. It means refusing to let it define your next step. You are not the sum of your inconsistency. You are the person pressing forward today. That's the only score that matters right now." },
    { v:"And I am certain that God, who began a good work within you, will continue his work until it is finally finished.", r:"Philippians 1:6", d:"God doesn't start projects and abandon them. He began something in you — the desire to grow, to be disciplined, to honor your body — and he is committed to finishing it. That's not pressure on you to be perfect. It's freedom. You don't have to hold yourself together. You just have to keep showing up, and trust that the One who started this knows how to finish it." },
    { v:"Seek the Kingdom of God above all else, and live righteously, and he will give you everything you need.", r:"Matthew 6:33", d:"Jesus said this to people anxious about basic needs. His answer wasn't 'stop needing things.' It was 'reorder what you seek first.' When God is genuinely first, everything else finds its proper place. Your training, your ambitions, your body goals — they become tools for a larger purpose instead of the scoreboard your worth is measured by. Seek first. Everything else follows." },
    { v:"Trust in the Lord with all your heart; do not depend on your own understanding. Seek his will in all you do, and he will show you which path to take.", r:"Proverbs 3:5–6", d:"Not leaning on your own understanding isn't asking you to be passive. It's asking you to hold your certainty loosely — to acknowledge that you don't have the full picture. In training: you might think you need to push harder when you need to rest. In life: the path you think is best might not be the one worth taking. Seek his will. Then trust the path that appears." },
    { v:"Commit your actions to the Lord, and your plans will succeed.", r:"Proverbs 16:3", d:"The word 'commit' here means to roll — like rolling a heavy burden onto someone stronger. You plan. You set goals. You show up. And then you roll the outcome onto God instead of white-knuckling it yourself. The work is yours. The results are his. That's not an excuse for laziness — it's the posture that makes sustained effort possible without burning out on anxiety." },
    { v:"Be strong and courageous! Do not be afraid and do not panic. For the Lord your God will personally go ahead of you.", r:"Deuteronomy 31:6", d:"Moses said this to a generation about to walk into something terrifying. The reason for the courage isn't 'you've got this.' It's 'he goes with you.' The hard workout, the new season, the thing that genuinely scares you — God is not watching from a distance. He goes personally ahead of you. Courage becomes possible when it's not sourced in your confidence but in the presence of someone who cannot be stopped." },
    { v:"You didn't choose me. I chose you. I appointed you to go and produce lasting fruit.", r:"John 15:16", d:"You didn't find your way to faith or to this training on your own. Something drew you. Someone called you. The choice precedes the calling — you were chosen before you made any move toward God. This changes the foundation you stand on. You're not building a resume of worthiness. You're responding to a selection that was already made. Produce lasting fruit from that security." },
    { v:"The Lord directs the steps of the godly. He delights in every detail of their lives.", r:"Psalm 37:23", d:"He delights in every detail. Not just the big things — the rep you finally hit, the sleep you prioritized, the morning you didn't want to get up but did. God is paying close attention to the ordinary. The ordinary is where most of life actually happens, and that's where his delight in you is most consistently present." },
    { v:"Look straight ahead, and fix your eyes on what lies before you.", r:"Proverbs 4:25", d:"Look straight ahead. Not at what someone else is doing. Not backward at who you used to be. Straight ahead — at the next rep, the next meal, the next faithful decision. Peripheral comparison and regret are two of the fastest ways to lose the road. Just the next step. That's all that's needed right now." },
    { v:"Take delight in the Lord, and he will give you your heart's desires.", r:"Psalm 37:4", d:"Delight is more than enjoyment — it's deep alignment. When you genuinely delight in God, your desires start to change from the inside. The things you want begin to match the things that are actually good for you. You may have started training for one reason and find, over time, that what you really wanted was discipline, resilience, and the quiet satisfaction of keeping your commitments. Delight shapes desire." },
    { v:"But those who trust in the Lord will find new strength. They will soar high on wings like eagles.", r:"Isaiah 40:31", d:"Isaiah wrote this to people who were genuinely depleted at the level of soul. The promise of new strength isn't conditional on you already having some. It's given to those who've run out. Trusting God with your training means releasing the need to perform, the anxiety about results, the pressure to earn your worth through effort. When you release that weight, something opens up. A different kind of strength becomes available." },
    { v:"I can do everything through Christ, who gives me strength.", r:"Philippians 4:13", d:"Paul wrote this from prison — not from his greatest success. He had learned through experience to find a strength that didn't depend on circumstances. This is what you're actually building: not just physical capacity, but the interior toughness that handles a bad day without collapsing. Christ's strength isn't extra horsepower added to your engine. It's a different engine entirely. Ask for it today." },
    { v:"Give all your worries and cares to God, for he cares about you.", r:"1 Peter 5:7", d:"The instruction is to cast — throw — your worries onto God. Not gently hand them over. Throw them, because they're heavy and God can handle what you cannot. The anxiety about whether the effort is working, whether your body is responding, whether you're on the right track — throw it. God's care for you is personal and specific. He can carry what's crushing you." },
    { v:"This is the day the Lord has made. We will rejoice and be glad in it.", r:"Psalm 118:24", d:"The day was made by God. That's the reason for rejoicing — not that the day is easy, not that you feel like it, not that everything is going well. The day itself is a gift from a God who is still making days, still holding them. You get to be in this one. That's enough reason to be glad. Show up to the day with the gratitude of someone who knows it wasn't guaranteed." },
    { v:"Don't be afraid, for I am with you. Don't be discouraged, for I am your God. I will strengthen you and help you.", r:"Isaiah 41:10", d:"God says 'I will' five times in this verse. I will strengthen. I will help. I will hold you. I will uphold you. Five declarations from a God who does not break promises. When the session is hard, when motivation is gone, when the season is dry — return to this list. You are not holding yourself up. You are being held." },
    { v:"Now all glory to God, who is able to accomplish infinitely more than we might ask or think.", r:"Ephesians 3:20", d:"Infinitely more than you ask or think. Most people's asking is too small. Modest goals. Modest prayers. But God's capacity to work in you is not bounded by your imagination. This doesn't mean set unrealistic expectations and coast. It means do the faithful, consistent work — and leave the ceiling open. Stay curious about what God might be building through this that you cannot yet see." },
    { v:"The Lord your God is living among you. He is a mighty savior. He will take great delight in you.", r:"Zephaniah 3:17", d:"He takes great delight in you. Right now. Not the version of you at your goal weight, not the version with the PR numbers you're chasing. You, as you actually are today. This is the love you're training from, not toward. You don't earn delight. You receive it. Let that change the energy you bring — someone who is already delighted in trains differently than someone desperate to become worthy of it." },
    { v:"The Lord is my shepherd; I have all that I need.", r:"Psalm 23:1", d:"A shepherd doesn't just provide — he leads, protects, and restores. The sheep doesn't plan the route or secure the food. That's the shepherd's role. You are invited into a posture of trust that doesn't require you to be the source of your own provision. Show up. Do the work. And trust that the One leading you knows where the green meadows are." },
    { v:"Taste and see that the Lord is good. Oh, the joys of those who take refuge in him!", r:"Psalm 34:8", d:"Taste and see. The invitation is to experience, not just believe from a distance. You can know intellectually that rest is important, that your body is worth caring for, that God is good. But knowing and experiencing are different. The experience of God's goodness is found in actually taking refuge — in stopping the striving, leaning into trust, and discovering that he holds you there." },
    { v:"And we know that God causes everything to work together for the good of those who love God.", r:"Romans 8:28", d:"Everything — not just the good sessions, not just the wins. Paul doesn't say everything is good. He says it works together for good. The setback has a purpose. The season that isn't going how you planned has a purpose. Nothing in the hands of God is wasted. Trust him with the parts of your journey that don't make sense yet." },
    { v:"With man this is impossible, but with God all things are possible.", r:"Matthew 19:26", d:"Jesus said this about something his disciples considered impossible. His point: the limit of human effort is never the limit of what God can do. Bring your impossible thing to God today. The habit that won't stick. The goal that feels too far. The version of yourself you've given up on. Hand it over. What's impossible in your own strength is possible in partnership with the God who makes things new." },
    { v:"So humble yourselves under the mighty power of God, and at the right time he will lift you up in honor.", r:"1 Peter 5:6", d:"Humility here means accurately knowing who holds what. You hold the effort. God holds the outcome and the timing. The lifting — the eventual honor — belongs to him to give. There's enormous pressure in your twenties and thirties to arrive, to achieve, to be seen. Humble yourself under the God who is more interested in who you're becoming than in how impressive you look while becoming it." },
    { v:"The Lord will work out his plans for my life — for your faithful love, O Lord, endures forever.", r:"Psalm 138:8", d:"He is already working out his plans. Past tense — already in motion, already active. The faithful love driving his plans never ends. That means on the days you're inconsistent, on the weeks where everything falls apart — his plans for your good are still being worked out. He hasn't paused. He hasn't given up." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and my song; he has given me victory.", r:"Exodus 15:2", d:"Strength and song together — discipline and joy aren't enemies. Training can be both hard and something you love. The effort can be real and the delight can be genuine. God is the source of both. Let your training be both hard work and genuine expression of who you are and what you've been given." },
    { v:"Wait patiently for the Lord. Be brave and courageous. Yes, wait patiently for the Lord.", r:"Psalm 27:14", d:"Patience requires courage. The world rewards urgency and the quick result. God's invitation is to brave patience — to trust that what is invisible is still growing. Progress in the body happens beneath the surface for weeks before it becomes visible. Character is the same. Be brave enough to wait. The waiting is the work." },
    { v:"He gives power to the weak and strength to the powerless.", r:"Isaiah 40:29", d:"Not to those who are already strong. To those who have run out. The promise is most relevant at the exact moment you feel most disqualified from receiving it. When the tank is empty, when motivation has evaporated — that is where this verse lives. God gives power to the weak. He meets you at the end of your reserves." },
    { v:"Be strong, and let your heart take courage, all you who wait for the Lord!", r:"Psalm 31:24", d:"Courage is a choice the heart makes, not a feeling that arrives. You don't wait for courage before you act. You choose it, and it shows up in the choosing. Every time you show up when you don't feel like it, every time you choose the harder right thing — you are training your heart to be courageous. It gets stronger the more you exercise it." },
  ],
  2: [
    { v:"Thank you for making me so wonderfully complex! Your workmanship is marvelous — how well I know it.", r:"Psalm 139:14", d:"David looked at his own body and responded with worship. Not self-critique. Not comparison. Worship. The body you're training today — the specific way it's put together, its particular strengths and limitations — was made by God with the same attention he gave to the rest of creation. You are not a project to be fixed. You are workmanship. There's a difference." },
    { v:"See how very much our Father loves us, for he calls us his children, and that is what we are!", r:"1 John 3:1", d:"The love of a parent for their child doesn't begin with what the child achieves. It precedes achievement entirely. Before you did anything, before you became anyone, you were called his child. That's not a title you earn. It's the most foundational identity you have. Everything else — athlete, professional, son, daughter — sits beneath this one. Train from the security of that identity." },
    { v:"For we are God's masterpiece. He has created us anew in Christ Jesus, so we can do the good things he planned for us long ago.", r:"Ephesians 2:10", d:"The Greek word here is poema — poem. You are not a rough draft. You are a poem being written by a master, shaped with intention, every word chosen carefully. Poems take time. They go through revisions. What looks unfinished in the middle is part of the process. Your body and your character are both works in progress. That is not a flaw. That is the nature of something being carefully made." },
    { v:"You are altogether beautiful, my darling, beautiful in every way.", r:"Song of Solomon 4:7", d:"This is not a compliment from someone who doesn't know you — it's from the One who made you. No qualifications, no conditions, no 'you would be beautiful if.' The word is now. Every part. Including the parts you're working on, the parts you're not happy with. God's view of you is not the view from the mirror. Let his view go deeper than the surface." },
    { v:"For you are a holy people, who belong to the Lord your God. The Lord your God has chosen you to be his own special treasure.", r:"Deuteronomy 7:6", d:"You are God's treasure. Not his project, not his problem. His treasure. That word implies something he values, guards, and takes delight in. When the world tries to reduce your worth to your output, your appearance, or your performance — this is the counter-word. Your value was established before you produced anything at all." },
    { v:"But you are a chosen people. You are royal priests, a holy nation, God's very own possession.", r:"1 Peter 2:9", d:"Royal priests. In the ancient world, priests carried something sacred on behalf of others. You carry something too — the image of God into every space you occupy. The health and strength you're building is not just for you. It equips you to serve, to sustain relationships, to show up fully for the people in your life." },
    { v:"You have not received a spirit that makes you fearful slaves. Instead, you received God's Spirit when he adopted you as his own children.", r:"Romans 8:15", d:"Fear-based motivation is exhausting. Training to punish yourself, to control something, to outrun shame — it burns out. The Spirit you received is not a slave driver. It's an adoption into family. Children play hard, rest without guilt, ask for help when they're tired. Train as a child who belongs, not as a slave trying to earn what's already been given." },
    { v:"God created human beings in his own image. In the image of God he created them; male and female he created them.", r:"Genesis 1:27", d:"You bear the image of God — imago Dei — before you've done anything with it. This is the first thing Scripture says about human beings. Before sin, before failure, before any of it. You were made to reflect something of God into the world: strength, creativity, resilience, care, dignity. Every time you recover and show up again, you're reflecting the image of a God who is faithful and does not quit." },
    { v:"My old self has been crucified with Christ. It is no longer I who live, but Christ lives in me.", r:"Galatians 2:20", d:"Paul is not talking about a self-improvement program. He's talking about a death and a resurrection. The old patterns, the old shame, the identity built on performance and approval — crucified. What lives now is animated by Christ himself. This is why lasting transformation comes from the inside out. You can change habits, but only Christ can change your identity. And from a new identity, new habits aren't just possible — they're natural." },
    { v:"And because you belong to him, the power of the life-giving Spirit has freed you from the power of sin that leads to death.", r:"Romans 8:2", d:"Freedom. The Spirit that raised Jesus from the dead lives in you — not just near you, not just available to you. In you. Let it produce freedom in how you relate to your body: not as a warden enforcing punishment, not as a critic cataloguing flaws, but as someone alive and free in a temple belonging to a living God." },
    { v:"Don't copy the behavior and customs of this world, but let God transform you into a new person by changing the way you think.", r:"Romans 12:2", d:"Your mind is a training ground. What you rehearse there, you become. The world has a script about bodies — what they should look like, what they're for, what gives them value. Transformation begins when that script is replaced. Not by ignoring reality, but by letting God rewrite the framework. Ask him to renew the way you think about your body. The changed mind produces the changed life." },
    { v:"For God has not given us a spirit of fear and timidity, but of power, love, and self-discipline.", r:"2 Timothy 1:7", d:"Power, love, and self-discipline — three gifts given together. The self-discipline described here isn't the gritted-teeth effort of someone barely holding on. It flows from the same source as power and love. It's a gift of the Spirit, not a product of willpower alone. Ask for it today, then act from the asking." },
    { v:"You made all the delicate, inner parts of my body and knit me together in my mother's womb.", r:"Psalm 139:13", d:"God didn't use a template when he made you. He knit you — stitch by specific stitch, cell by cell, with care and intention. The particular way you're put together: the way you learn, the way you move, your specific strengths and limitations — all of it was knit deliberately. You are not a mistake or an accident. You are a specific, intentional work. Honor that today." },
    { v:"How precious are your thoughts about me, O God. They cannot be numbered!", r:"Psalm 139:17", d:"He is thinking about you right now. Not cataloguing your failures or calculating your performance. Thinking about you — with the attention a craftsman gives to the thing he loves most. The thoughts are too many to count. You are not an afterthought. You are thought about constantly, tenderly, by the One who made you. Train from that." },
    { v:"People judge by outward appearance, but the Lord looks at the heart.", r:"1 Samuel 16:7", d:"The world will always have a measuring stick for your body. God's measuring stick is different. He looks at the heart — the intention behind choices, the faithfulness in small moments, the love driving decisions. Are you training from a heart that wants to honor God and serve others? That's what matters most. Let the world's measuring sticks stay outside." },
    { v:"Charm is deceptive, and beauty does not last; but a woman who fears the Lord will be greatly praised.", r:"Proverbs 31:30", d:"The body changes. Strength ebbs and flows with seasons. Appearance shifts with age and life. But the person who orders their life around what is true and lasting — who fears God and lives accordingly — that person is praised by those who see clearly. What you're building in character outlasts every physical result. Build both, but know which one lasts." },
    { v:"She is clothed with strength and dignity, and she laughs without fear of the future.", r:"Proverbs 31:25", d:"Clothed with strength and dignity — not wearing it as costume, but wrapped in it. Moving through the world in it daily. The woman described in Proverbs 31 doesn't need the future to be certain before she can laugh. She laughs because she's secure. That security isn't arrogance. It's the settled confidence of someone who knows who holds tomorrow. Train to build that kind of strength." },
    { v:"For we live by believing and not by seeing.", r:"2 Corinthians 5:7", d:"Progress is often invisible before it becomes visible. The nervous system adapts before the muscle grows. Discipline forms before the result appears. Living by faith in training means continuing to show up when the evidence isn't there yet. The same is true in your relationship with God. Faith moves first. Sight follows. The invisible work is still real work." },
    { v:"I knew you before I formed you in your mother's womb. Before you were born I set you apart.", r:"Jeremiah 1:5", d:"Before you existed, you were known. Before your first breath, before you had done a single thing — known, formed, set apart by God. This is your origin story. Not the family you were born into, not the mistakes you've made. Before all of it: known and set apart. You were not an accident. You were an appointment." },
    { v:"The Spirit of God, who raised Jesus from the dead, lives in you.", r:"Romans 8:11", d:"The same power that split death open lives in your body right now. When you feel like you have nothing left, when the tank is empty, when motivation has completely gone — this is the resource. Not manufactured willpower. Not a pep talk. The power of resurrection, resident in you. Ask for it. It's already there." },
    { v:"And I am convinced that nothing can ever separate us from God's love.", r:"Romans 8:38", d:"Paul lists everything he can think of — death, life, angels, demons, fears, the highest heights, the deepest depths — and says: none of it separates you from the love of God in Christ. You may fail. You may disappear for months. The love doesn't waver. That's not permission to be careless — it's the security that makes genuine bravery possible." },
    { v:"Even before he made the world, God loved us and chose us in Christ to be holy and without fault in his eyes.", r:"Ephesians 1:4", d:"Before the world was made — before time, before matter — you were already in the heart of God. Loved. Chosen. Declared holy and without fault. Not because of what you would do, but because of what Christ would do. This is the love you come from. Let it be the atmosphere you train in, not a reward waiting at the end of it." },
    { v:"So now there is no condemnation for those who belong to Christ Jesus.", r:"Romans 8:1", d:"None. Not less condemnation, not reduced condemnation. None. If you carry condemnation into the gym — shame about your body, guilt about missed days, contempt for where you are — that condemnation is not from God. It is a lie. There is no case against you. No verdict of 'not enough.' Train from freedom, not from guilt." },
    { v:"Your real life is hidden with Christ in God.", r:"Colossians 3:3", d:"Hidden with Christ in God. There is something profoundly safe about that image. The truest version of who you are is not determined by the mirror, the number, or the achievement. It is hidden — held safely — in Christ. This is what you protect when you refuse comparison, train for health rather than approval, rest without guilt. Your real life is already secure." },
    { v:"We are citizens of heaven, where the Lord Jesus Christ lives.", r:"Philippians 3:20", d:"You hold dual citizenship. You are here, in this body, in this world — and that matters enormously. But you are also a citizen of a kingdom that does not end, and that shapes how you live here. You are not building a kingdom of personal achievement. You are stewarding a body and life that belong to a larger story. Let that perspective change what you're training for." },
    { v:"God saved us and called us to live a holy life — not because we deserved it, but because that was his plan.", r:"2 Timothy 1:9", d:"You were called. Intentionally, specifically, before you did anything to deserve it. The calling is to a holy life — set apart, purposeful, whole. Not because you earned it. Because it was his plan. You are walking in a purpose older than you are. Let that settle the question of whether you belong here, whether you're doing enough, whether it's worth it." },
    { v:"Search me, O God, and know my heart; test me and know my anxious thoughts.", r:"Psalm 139:23", d:"Come in, look at everything, know what's actually there. The prayer of complete openness — no hiding, no performance, no curated version of yourself presented to God. This kind of honesty is the foundation of real transformation. You cannot change what you will not honestly examine. Ask God to search you today — not to condemn what he finds, but to heal it." },
    { v:"Point out anything in me that offends you, and lead me along the path of everlasting life.", r:"Psalm 139:24", d:"The path of everlasting life is not a road to a destination. It is a way of walking now — with integrity, with wholeness, with attention to what is true and good. Ask God to lead you on it. In how you train, how you rest, how you speak to yourself about your body. The path is already laid. Stay on it, one faithful day at a time." },
  ],
  3: [
    { v:"Create in me a clean heart, O God. Renew a loyal spirit within me.", r:"Psalm 51:10", d:"David prayed this after his greatest failure — and notice: he didn't ask God to fix his circumstances. He asked God to renew him. External change without internal renewal doesn't last. You can change your schedule, your diet, your program — and still find the same patterns returning if the heart underneath hasn't changed. Ask for the clean heart first. The changed habits grow from it." },
    { v:"Though our bodies are dying, our spirits are being renewed every day.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:16", d:"The outer person is declining — that's just true. Every body eventually weakens. Paul isn't in denial about it. What he's pointing to is the other thing happening simultaneously: daily renewal of the inner person. The investment in your body matters. But the investment in who you're becoming spiritually has a longer return. Both are worth tending. One lasts longer." },
    { v:"The Holy Spirit produces this kind of fruit in our lives: love, joy, peace, patience, kindness, goodness, faithfulness, gentleness, and self-control.", r:"Galatians 5:22–23", d:"Self-control is the last fruit listed — perhaps because it grows from everything before it. Love, joy, peace, patience — these are the soil in which sustainable self-discipline grows. Willpower alone has shallow roots. When self-control is rooted in love for God and genuine delight in who you're becoming, it goes deeper and lasts much longer." },
    { v:"For you know that when your faith is tested, your endurance has a chance to grow.", r:"James 1:3", d:"Endurance doesn't grow in comfort. It grows in the exact place you don't want to be — in the middle of the test. The hard session that makes you want to quit is the one building endurance. The week where motivation evaporates and you show up anyway is the one cementing the habit. You are not in the wrong place when it gets hard. You are in precisely the right place." },
    { v:"So let it grow, for when your endurance is fully developed, you will be perfect and complete, needing nothing.", r:"James 1:4", d:"Perfect and complete — the image is of something that has reached its full development. The process is the point. Every stage of your development matters. The beginner stage, the plateau, the breakthrough — all of it is part of becoming whole. You are not behind. You are in the process of becoming, and the process, patiently engaged, leads somewhere real." },
    { v:"No discipline is enjoyable while it is happening — it's painful! But afterward there will be a peaceful harvest of right living.", r:"Hebrews 12:11", d:"The author doesn't pretend discipline is fun. He says it's painful. The soreness is real. The early alarm is real. The session you don't want to do is real. He doesn't minimize any of it. What he does is point to the afterward — a harvest. Something grows in the soil of consistent, faithful discipline that cannot grow any other way. Stay in the process." },
    { v:"Plant the good seeds of righteousness, and you will harvest a crop of love.", r:"Hosea 10:12", d:"Seeds are small and invisible in the ground, and they require waiting. Every rep you log is a seed. Every rest day you honor is a seed. Every time you choose nourishment over punishment, patience over comparison — you are planting. The harvest doesn't come all at once. It comes as the seed has time to take root. Keep planting." },
    { v:"Work hard to show the results of your salvation, obeying God with deep reverence and fear.", r:"Philippians 2:12", d:"Work it out — not earn it. Salvation is given; your response to it is the working out. The same principle applies to the health you have access to: the potential for a stronger, more capable body is available to you today. But you have to work it out. You have to show up. Grace does not eliminate effort — it empowers it." },
    { v:"For God is working in you, giving you the desire and the power to do what pleases him.", r:"Philippians 2:13", d:"The desire and the power — both are gifts. When you feel a pull toward consistency, toward health, toward honoring your body — that pull may be God's work in you. You are not manufacturing the motivation alone. He is giving it. And when the desire is gone, this verse is the one to stand on: the power is still available even when the feeling isn't. Ask for it. Then act anyway." },
    { v:"When troubles come your way, consider it an opportunity for great joy.", r:"James 1:2", d:"James is not telling you to fake positivity. He's inviting a reframe: what if every obstacle is actually an opening? The plateau is an invitation to learn. The injury is an invitation to rest. The hard season is training ground for the person you're becoming. Not every hard thing is punishment. Some of it is preparation." },
    { v:"If you need wisdom, ask our generous God, and he will give it to you. He will not rebuke you for asking.", r:"James 1:5", d:"You are allowed to ask. God is not stingy with wisdom — not about your training, not about your career, not about relationships. He gives generously, without rebuke. You don't have to pretend to have it figured out. Bring your questions honestly. Then pay attention to the answers that come through experience, through coaches, through the slow wisdom of a body learning itself." },
    { v:"I have hidden your word in my heart, that I might not sin against you.", r:"Psalm 119:11", d:"Hidden here means internalized — not just memorized. The word of God hidden in the heart is what shapes the instincts, what the voice in your head reaches for first. What you rehearse regularly becomes what you are. The habits you build in training are being hidden in the body the same way — in muscle memory, in rhythms. Practice what's worth practicing." },
    { v:"Your word is a lamp to guide my feet and a light for my path.", r:"Psalm 119:105", d:"A lamp shows you the next step — not the whole road. You don't need to see the entire journey from here to your goal. You need enough light for today. What is the next faithful step? The next session. The next meal. The next rest. The path is illuminated one step at a time. Walk in the light you have." },
    { v:"Since we are living by the Spirit, let us follow the Spirit's leading in every part of our lives.", r:"Galatians 5:25", d:"Every part — not just the obviously spiritual ones. The way you move, eat, sleep, rest, recover — the Spirit can and should lead all of it. A Spirit-led approach to your body is not one of punishment or obsession, but of discernment: what does this body actually need today? That kind of wisdom is available. Ask. Then listen." },
    { v:"Let us not neglect our meeting together, as some people do, but encourage one another.", r:"Hebrews 10:25", d:"We are not meant to pursue health, faith, or growth alone. The community around you — your coach, the people who know your goals — these are not optional extras. They are part of the design. Encouragement is most powerful when it's specific and in person, when someone says 'you can do this' and you believe them. Don't disappear from the people who are for you." },
    { v:"Keep putting into practice all you learned and received. Then the God of peace will be with you.", r:"Philippians 4:9", d:"Practice — not just learn. There is a difference between knowing good form and practicing it until it's automatic. Between knowing rest is important and actually resting. The peace of God accompanies the practicing, not just the knowing. What do you know to be true that you haven't yet put into practice? Start there." },
    { v:"Let your roots grow down into him, and let your lives be built on him. Then your faith will grow strong.", r:"Colossians 2:7", d:"Roots go down before branches go up. The invisible part — underground, in the dark — is what makes the visible growth possible. Your private faithfulness — the consistent sessions, the genuine prayer — is root work. No one sees most of it. But it is what makes the growth possible. Let your roots go deep before you demand visible fruit." },
    { v:"This same God who takes care of me will supply all your needs from his glorious riches.", r:"Philippians 4:19", d:"Generously provides — not exactly enough, but generously, with surplus for sharing. You are being resourced for more than yourself. The strength, the health, the energy you're building has overflow for others. The people in your life need you to be whole. Let that reframe the training: you are building something that can overflow." },
    { v:"Think clearly and exercise self-control. Look forward to the gracious salvation that will come to you.", r:"1 Peter 1:13", d:"Clear thinking and self-control — both are practices, not passive states. Clear thinking requires intentionality about what you consume, how you rest, what you rehearse in your mind. Self-control is strengthened by repeated, deliberate choices. Every time you choose the training session over the excuse — you are practicing. These compound over time." },
    { v:"Warn each other every day, while it is still today, so that none of you will be deceived by sin and hardened against God.", r:"Hebrews 3:13", d:"Today. The accountability that prevents drift needs to be current. Gradual drift is how hardness sets in — daily, in small increments. Stay soft today. Stay connected to people who know your goals and will speak honestly to you. Today is the day to tend the relationships that keep you on the right road." },
    { v:"We are being transformed into his image with ever-increasing glory.", r:"2 Corinthians 3:18", d:"Transformation by contemplation. You become what you behold. What you fix your attention on shapes you over time. Fix your attention on Christ — his strength, his endurance, his faithfulness. Let those qualities form in you not by striving to imitate them but by genuinely looking at him. The looking is the practice." },
    { v:"Those who live to please the Spirit will harvest everlasting life.", r:"Galatians 6:8", d:"The harvest principle applies physically too. Those who live by cravings — the shortcut, the avoidance of anything uncomfortable — tend toward decay. Those who consistently sow to the Spirit — showing up, making choices that build rather than erode — harvest life. Not just in the body. In the whole person. Sow to life today." },
    { v:"So let's not get tired of doing what is good. At just the right time we will reap a harvest of blessing if we don't give up.", r:"Galatians 6:9", d:"The temptation to give up often comes just before the harvest. The plant looks the same above ground for weeks, and then suddenly — fruit. The body adapts on its own timeline. Character forms in the hidden places before it shows in the visible ones. Don't give up. Keep doing the good. The timing is not in your hands — the faithfulness is." },
    { v:"Just as you accepted Christ Jesus as your Lord, you must continue to follow him.", r:"Colossians 2:6", d:"Continue. The beginning was a decision, but the ongoing life is a series of decisions — daily, mundane, consistent choices to keep walking in the same direction. The beginning is often fueled by excitement. The continuation is what actually transforms. Keep following, even when the excitement has settled into ordinary faithfulness." },
    { v:"Work willingly at whatever you do, as though you were working for the Lord rather than for people.", r:"Colossians 3:23", d:"Willingly — not reluctantly, not resentfully, not with one eye on whether anyone notices. The session no one will praise you for, the discipline no one sees — that's where real character is built. The Lord sees it. And working for him rather than for people is a standard that doesn't depend on recognition to stay motivated." },
    { v:"God blesses those who patiently endure testing and temptation.", r:"James 1:12", d:"Patient endurance is what you need now. Not breakthrough energy, not dramatic transformation — patient endurance. The steady, consistent, unflashy showing up. The blessing promised here doesn't come to those who sprinted fastest at the beginning. It comes to those who didn't quit. You need what you need now: to not quit." },
    { v:"Don't just listen to God's word. You must do what it says.", r:"James 1:22", d:"Knowledge without action is the most comfortable form of self-deception. You can know exactly what to do and still not do it. James identifies the gap between hearing and doing as the place where we fool ourselves. What do you know today that you need to do? Close the gap. Not perfectly. Not all at once. But today." },
    { v:"Don't reject the Lord's discipline, and don't be upset when he corrects you. For the Lord corrects those he loves.", r:"Proverbs 3:11–12", d:"Discipline from a loving God looks different from punishment from an indifferent authority. It's targeted, purposeful, motivated by love. When something needs to change — when progress stalls, when patterns need addressing — receive it as correction from a Father, not condemnation from a judge. Ask what needs adjusting. Be willing to receive the answer." },
    { v:"Joyful are those who obey his laws and search for him with all their hearts.", r:"Psalm 119:2", d:"Wholehearted searching — not casual interest but active, sustained seeking. The joy described here is the joy of someone fully engaged. Bring that same energy to your health: search for what works, seek understanding about your body, pursue growth with your whole heart. Joy is the companion of wholehearted pursuit, not of arrival." },
    { v:"Be strong and immovable. Always work enthusiastically for the Lord, for nothing you do for the Lord is ever useless.", r:"1 Corinthians 15:58", d:"Nothing is useless. Not the session no one saw. Not the consistent week no one celebrated. Not the faithful habit that hasn't yet produced visible results. In God's economy, faithful work is never wasted — it is counted, it accumulates, it compounds into something. Be strong and immovable in your faithfulness." },
    { v:"After you have suffered a little while, he will restore, support, and strengthen you, and place you on a firm foundation.", r:"1 Peter 5:10", d:"After. The suffering is not the end of the story — it's a chapter. God's response to it is active: he restores, supports, strengthens, establishes. The foundation you're building — in your body, in your faith, in your character — is being set firm by the One who has the longest view. Trust the process." },
  ],
  4: [
    { v:"He is not here! He is risen from the dead, just as he said would happen.", r:"Matthew 28:6", d:"The most important sentence in human history, delivered to two women at dawn after the worst weekend imaginable. They came expecting a grave and found it empty — not robbed but conquered. Every time you return after an injury, every time you get back up after being knocked down — you are living in the echo of this morning. Resurrection is the shape of the Christian life. Keep getting up." },
    { v:"We are pressed on every side by troubles, but we are not crushed. We are perplexed, but not driven to despair.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:8", d:"Pressed but not crushed. Perplexed but not despairing. Paul describes a life that is genuinely hard — not a life where everything has been made smooth. The hope of the gospel is not the absence of pressure. It is the strange, sustaining resilience that keeps something alive in the middle of it. You will have hard days. The question is whether they will crush you or press you into something stronger." },
    { v:"We get knocked down, but we are not destroyed.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:9", d:"Knocked down but not destroyed. This is the testimony of everyone who has ever come back from something real. You are not destroyed by the knock down. You are shaped by the getting back up. The resilience you're building — the capacity to recover, to adapt, to come back — mirrors something the gospel has been teaching all along. You cannot be permanently put down." },
    { v:"I want to know Christ and experience the mighty power that raised him from the dead.", r:"Philippians 3:10", d:"The power that raised a dead body is available to living ones. Paul is not speaking abstractly — he wants to experience that power in his body, in his daily life. When you hit the wall, when the tank is genuinely empty — this is the power to call on. Not manufactured willpower. Not a second wind you work for. Resurrection power, given freely. Ask for it." },
    { v:"Our bodies are buried in weakness, but they will be raised in strength.", r:"1 Corinthians 15:43", d:"The body you're training today — with its limitations, its injuries, its imperfections — is seed. What is buried in weakness will be raised in strength. This is not an excuse to neglect the body now. It is a reason to honor it with appropriate perspective. You are tending something that will ultimately be made glorious. The gap between where you are and where you're going is one only God can close." },
    { v:"Thanks be to God! He gives us the victory through our Lord Jesus Christ.", r:"1 Corinthians 15:57", d:"Not to the already strong. To the weak. Not to the already victorious. To those in the middle of the fight. The victory is given — not achieved by performance. That shifts everything about how you approach the hard things. Not 'I have to win this.' But 'I'm already on the winning side — now let me live accordingly.' Train from victory, not toward it." },
    { v:"So be strong and immovable. Always work enthusiastically for the Lord.", r:"1 Corinthians 15:58", d:"The resurrection life is not passive or timid. It's adventurous. It expects things. It leans into the future rather than cowering from it. You have received life through resurrection — not a maintenance plan. Actual life. Let that reality make you bolder in your training, your goals, and the risks you're willing to take in the direction of who you're becoming." },
    { v:"Because of our faith, Christ has brought us into this place of undeserved privilege where we now stand.", r:"Romans 5:2", d:"Undeserved privilege — the grace of access. You stand in a place you did not earn. The door to God's presence, to his strength, to his renewal — open because of Christ, not because of your consistency. On the days you miss sessions, the weeks where everything falls apart — your access to God does not close. Train from that privilege." },
    { v:"We can rejoice when we run into problems and trials, for we know that they help us develop endurance.", r:"Romans 5:3", d:"Rejoice doesn't mean pretend the problem isn't there. It means choose a different frame — one you have to actively work at. The problem is developing something that cannot be built any other way. Endurance is the fruit of sustained difficulty. Every hard session, every plateau, every week where you showed up despite everything — you are building something inside them." },
    { v:"And endurance develops strength of character, and character strengthens our confident hope of salvation.", r:"Romans 5:4", d:"The chain: trial → endurance → character → hope. Nothing is wasted. The trial is not just pain — it is the beginning of a sequence that ends in hope. The character being formed through your consistency and faithfulness is load-bearing. It holds the hope in place when circumstances would otherwise collapse it." },
    { v:"And this hope will not lead to disappointment. For we know how dearly God loves us.", r:"Romans 5:5", d:"Hope rooted in God's love does not disappoint — because it is not hope in outcomes. It's hope in a Person. You may hope for specific results and be disappointed. But the hope that rests in the love of God — the assurance that you are known, valued, and held — that holds. Build your training on something deeper than results." },
    { v:"I pray that God, the source of hope, will fill you completely with joy and peace because you trust in him.", r:"Romans 15:13", d:"Joy and peace are not manufactured by you. They are received. They come as you trust — not as a reward for great performance, but as the natural overflow of a life leaning into God. The joy in this verse is not circumstantial happiness. It lives inside the hard season. Ask for it. It is available to those who trust." },
    { v:"Let all that I am wait quietly before God, for my hope is in him.", r:"Psalm 62:5", d:"Wait quietly — not passively. There is a quality of stillness in this hope that does not scramble or grasp. It waits with settled confidence. Your recovery days are practice in this. Your rest is not the absence of trust — it is the practice of it. Lie down. Let the body repair. Trust the process. Wait quietly before God." },
    { v:"He alone is my rock and my salvation, my fortress where I will not be shaken.", r:"Psalm 62:6", d:"When your identity is rooted in something that cannot move — a rock — you become unshakeable in a different way. Not because nothing hard happens. But because the thing your life is built on does not shift. Bad weeks, slow progress, the voice that says you are not enough — none of these can shake someone built on a rock. Build your identity on Christ, not on your performance." },
    { v:"Why am I discouraged? Why is my heart so sad? I will put my hope in God!", r:"Psalm 42:11", d:"The Psalmist talks to himself. He names the discouragement out loud, then redirects it deliberately. This is one of the most practical spiritual practices there is: catching the spiral and choosing to reorient. You are allowed to name the discouragement. Then talk back to it with something true. Not because you feel it — because it is true." },
    { v:"O Lord, you alone are my hope. I've trusted you, O Lord, from childhood.", r:"Psalm 71:5", d:"Hope in God is not a last resort — it's the foundation. Not hope in the outcome of your training, not hope that results will come. Hope in God himself, which holds regardless of how everything else turns out. That kind of hope doesn't disappoint. Build on it." },
    { v:"I will keep on hoping for your help; I will praise you more and more.", r:"Psalm 71:14", d:"Keep on — a commitment renewed, not a feeling sustained. Hope is the choice you make again and again, in every ordinary day, when circumstances aren't cooperating. Praise that increases — that doubles and redoubles — is the response of someone who has found that hope held. Let your praise grow in proportion to what God has sustained you through." },
    { v:"The Lord is good to those who depend on him, to those who search for him.", r:"Lamentations 3:25", d:"He is good — actively, specifically — to those who depend on him. Not to those who have it figured out. To those who depend. That posture of dependence — actually leaning your weight on God rather than maintaining self-sufficiency — is what opens you to his goodness. Depend. Seek. Receive what's available there." },
    { v:"So it is good to wait quietly for salvation from the Lord.", r:"Lamentations 3:26", d:"Quietly. Not anxiously. Not frantically. Quiet waiting is an act of trust — it declares: I believe the outcome is in hands more capable than mine. The recovery day is quiet waiting. The week you hold steady without visible progress is quiet waiting. God calls it good. Not frustrating. Good." },
    { v:"Our present troubles are small and won't last very long. Yet they produce for us a glory that vastly outweighs them.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:17", d:"Small and momentary — Paul used these words about troubles that included shipwreck and beatings. He had a longer perspective than most of us develop. Whatever the current struggle is, it is producing something in you that outlasts the struggle. The present trouble is doing more than it looks like it's doing." },
    { v:"We fix our gaze on things that cannot be seen. For the things we see now will soon be gone, but the things we cannot see will last forever.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:18", d:"Fix your gaze — an active, intentional choice about where you direct your attention. The visible things are real, but not the whole story. Fix your gaze on what is invisible: the character being formed, the faithfulness being established, the God who sees what is not yet visible. The practice of hope is the practice of looking in the right direction." },
    { v:"Always be full of joy in the Lord. I say it again — rejoice!", r:"Philippians 4:4", d:"Say it twice. The repetition suggests this takes effort — it's not a passive emotional state but a deliberate orientation. Joy in the Lord is not dependent on circumstances. It is rooted in who the Lord is. You can be joyful on a bad training day. You can rejoice in a season of slow progress. Because the joy is not in the progress — it is in the Lord who holds you through it." },
    { v:"I have told you all this so that you may have peace in me. Take heart, because I have overcome the world.", r:"John 16:33", d:"Take heart. Jesus doesn't promise the trials won't come. He promises they are already defeated. The world that tells you your body is not enough, that your worth depends on your output — that world has already been overcome. You train in the aftermath of a victory already won. Live accordingly." },
    { v:"No, despite all these things, overwhelming victory is ours through Christ, who loved us.", r:"Romans 8:37", d:"Despite all these things. Despite trouble, hardship, the hard season, the disappointing result. Despite. Not because everything worked out. Despite everything that didn't. The victory is not dependent on circumstances going your way. It belongs to you through Christ who loved you. You are on the winning side, even in the middle of the struggle." },
    { v:"For every child of God defeats this evil world, and we achieve this victory through our faith.", r:"1 John 5:4", d:"Faith defeats the world — not by escaping it but by seeing through it. The world's values — worth measured by performance, beauty defined by comparison, identity determined by achievement — faith sees through all of it. You are more than what you produce. More than the number. More than the result. That faith is itself a form of overcoming." },
    { v:"The Spirit who lives in you is greater than the spirit who lives in the world.", r:"1 John 4:4", d:"The Spirit in you is greater. Greater than the voices of shame. Greater than the comparison trap. Greater than the lie that you're not enough. You belong to God. The same Spirit that raised Jesus from the dead is alive in you. Train from that identity." },
    { v:"For our present troubles are producing for us a glory that vastly outweighs them and will last forever!", r:"2 Corinthians 4:17", d:"Our present troubles are producing something. They're not random. They're not purposeless. They're producing — active verb, present tense — a glory that will make the current weight feel light. Hold this perspective when the hard thing is hard. It is producing something. Stay in the process long enough to see what." },
    { v:"Being confident of this, that he who began a good work in you will carry it on to completion.", r:"Philippians 1:6", d:"He finishes what he begins. He does not abandon projects. He does not lose interest in who you're becoming. The good work in you is ongoing. You are a work in progress, and the Artist has not walked away from the canvas. Trust the process. He's still working." },
    { v:"The Lord is my light and my salvation — so why should I be afraid?", r:"Psalm 27:1", d:"Light and salvation from the same source. In seasons where it's hard to see what is working or where you're going — the Lord is the light. Not a feeling. Not a result. The Lord himself. Why should you be afraid? With this light, the question is real, and the answer is: you shouldn't be." },
    { v:"Everything written in the Scriptures was written to teach us, so that we might have hope.", r:"Romans 15:4", d:"Everything written in Scripture was written to teach us so that we might have hope. The stories of people who endured, pressed on, returned after falling — they were written for you. You are not the first person to find this hard. You are not alone. A whole cloud of witnesses has gone before you. Learn from their endurance." },
  ],
  5: [
    { v:"This is my command — be strong and courageous! Do not be afraid or discouraged. For the Lord your God is with you wherever you go.", r:"Joshua 1:9", d:"Three commands: be strong, be courageous, don't be afraid. Then the reason: the Lord your God is with you. The courage doesn't come from self-confidence — it comes from the presence of someone who cannot be stopped. Into every hard session, every season of doubt. Wherever you go — not just the easy places. He is there. What courageous action becomes possible because of that?" },
    { v:"Be on guard. Stand firm in the faith. Be courageous. Be strong.", r:"1 Corinthians 16:13", d:"Four imperatives: watch, stand, be courageous, be strong. Not suggestions. Commands. Be on guard against the voices that diminish you. Stand firm in what you know is true. Be courageous enough to do what's hard. Be strong — not in your own willpower alone, but in the strength that comes from something greater than you." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and my song; he has given me victory.", r:"Exodus 15:2", d:"Strength and song together — discipline and joy aren't opposites. Training can be both hard and something you love. The effort can be real and the delight can be genuine. God is the source of both. Let your training be both hard work and genuine delight in the work. They're not mutually exclusive." },
    { v:"Be strong in the Lord and in his mighty power.", r:"Ephesians 6:10", d:"Strong in the Lord — not in your own discipline or consistency. In the Lord. This is the distinction that makes sustainable strength possible. Your willpower is a limited resource. His mighty power is not. When you reach the edge of your own capacity, you have not reached the edge of what's available. Draw from him." },
    { v:"God is our refuge and strength, always ready to help in times of trouble.", r:"Psalm 46:1", d:"Always ready — not sometimes available, not on-call during official spiritual hours. Always ready to help in the trouble, not just before it. The hard session is not evidence of God's absence. It may be exactly where his presence is most accessible — because that's where you most need it. Go into the hard thing knowing you're not going alone." },
    { v:"The Lord gives his people strength. The Lord blesses them with peace.", r:"Psalm 29:11", d:"Strength and peace given together. Not one or the other. The God who gives strength for the effort also gives peace for the recovery. These are not competing gifts — they're from the same source. Receive strength for the work. Receive peace for the rest. Both are his to give. Both are yours to receive." },
    { v:"My health may fail, and my spirit may grow weak, but God remains the strength of my heart.", r:"Psalm 73:26", d:"My health may fail. The Psalmist isn't in denial about what the body can and cannot guarantee. He's pointing to the heart — the deep center — and saying that even when the outer fails, the inner strength holds. As you build physical capacity, build also the interior strength that will sustain you when the outer eventually fades. God is that inner strength." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and my shield. I trust him with all my heart.", r:"Psalm 28:7", d:"Strength for the effort, shield for the vulnerability. You need both. The strength to push hard, and the protection of knowing you're not exposed when you're weak. Trust him with all your heart — not just the confident parts, but the parts that doubt, the parts that are afraid. He is both strength and shield for all of it." },
    { v:"He gives power to the weak and strength to the powerless.", r:"Isaiah 40:29", d:"To the weak. To the powerless. Not to the already capable. The recipients of this promise are people at the end of their resources. If that's you today — if you're running genuinely low — this promise is specifically for you. God does not wait for you to get stronger before he helps. He meets you at the bottom." },
    { v:"Don't be afraid, for I am with you. Don't be discouraged, for I am your God. I will strengthen you and help you.", r:"Isaiah 41:10", d:"Five 'I wills' in one verse. I will strengthen. I will help. I will hold you. I will uphold you. Five declarations from a God who does not break promises. When you hit the wall — the plateau, the season where nothing seems to be working — return to this list. You are not holding yourself up. You are being held." },
    { v:"For I hold you by your right hand — I, the Lord your God. And I say to you, Don't be afraid. I am here to help you.", r:"Isaiah 41:13", d:"Made perfect in weakness. God's power is not supplementary to your strength — it fills in where your strength ends. Your limitation is not an obstacle to God's work. It is the exact space where his power shows up most clearly. Don't hide your weakness. Offer it. It is precisely there that his power will be most evident." },
    { v:"The Sovereign Lord is my strength! He makes me as surefooted as a deer, able to tread upon the heights.", r:"Habakkuk 3:19", d:"With God I can scale a wall. David wrote this about literal military victories — and the principle transfers. The goal that seems too far. The version of yourself that seems unreachable. The wall in front of you today is scalable. Not easily. Not without effort. But with God — actually possible." },
    { v:"Through God we will do valiantly, and it is he who shall tread down our foes.", r:"Psalm 60:12", d:"Through God we will do valiantly — not cautiously, not half-heartedly, but with courage that doesn't hold back. The valor here is not recklessness. It's wholehearted effort in partnership with One who goes before you. Bring everything you have today. Do it in his strength." },
    { v:"I can do everything through Christ, who gives me strength.", r:"Philippians 4:13", d:"Paul said this having learned it through experience — through seasons of plenty and seasons of nothing. The strength he's describing is not extra horsepower. It's a different engine entirely. Whatever you're facing today — ask for the strength that doesn't depend on circumstances cooperating." },
    { v:"My grace is sufficient for you, for my power is made perfect in weakness.", r:"2 Corinthians 12:9", d:"The power of God fills in where your strength ends. Your limitation is not a problem God has to work around. It is the location where his power is most perfectly displayed. Stop trying to hide the limitation. Bring it honestly. That's where he shows up." },
    { v:"Therefore I will boast all the more gladly about my weaknesses, so that Christ's power may rest on me.", r:"2 Corinthians 12:9", d:"Paul boasts in weakness because that's where Christ's power is most evident. This is counterintuitive — most people work hard to hide weakness, to project strength, to look like they have it together. What would it look like to stop hiding your limitations and start letting God work in them?" },
    { v:"With your help I can advance against a troop; with my God I can scale a wall.", r:"Psalm 18:29", d:"The wall in front of you — the goal that seems too high, the standard you can't quite reach — it is scalable. Not by you alone. But with the One who has already been on the other side of every wall you'll ever face." },
    { v:"The Lord will fight for you; you need only to be still.", r:"Exodus 14:14", d:"The Lord will fight for you — you need only be still. Moses said this to people who could see the army behind them and the sea in front. Their options looked like zero. And the answer was: be still. Some of the most courageous things you can do is stop striving in your own strength. You do your part. Let God do what you cannot." },
    { v:"No, despite all these things, overwhelming victory is ours through Christ, who loved us.", r:"Romans 8:37", d:"Overwhelming victory — not modest victory, not barely-made-it victory. Overwhelming. More than needed. The love of Christ does not just rescue you from defeat. It positions you in victory. Whatever you're facing today — this is the ground you stand on. You are more than a conqueror. Act like it." },
    { v:"For every child of God defeats this evil world, and we achieve this victory through our faith.", r:"1 John 5:4", d:"Faith defeats the world's system — the system that measures your worth by output, your beauty by comparison, your value by performance. Every person who lives from a different set of values is overcoming. You overcome when you train from identity instead of insecurity. When you rest without guilt. When you set goals from abundance instead of desperation." },
    { v:"You belong to God. You have already won a victory, because the Spirit who lives in you is greater than the spirit who lives in the world.", r:"1 John 4:4", d:"The Spirit in you is greater — not slightly more powerful. Greater. Whatever opposes you, whatever voice tells you you're not enough — the Spirit in you exceeds it. You belong to God. Train from that identity. The greater One lives in you." },
    { v:"I go before you and will level the mountains; I will break down gates of bronze and cut through bars of iron.", r:"Isaiah 45:2", d:"He goes before you. The new season, the new goal, the unfamiliar challenge — God has already been there. You are not stepping into uncharted territory. You're following someone who has already walked it. The path ahead has already been trodden by someone who will not abandon you. Follow without fear." },
    { v:"Be strong and courageous, for you are the one who will lead these people.", r:"Joshua 1:6", d:"For the sake of others. The courage being called for here isn't just personal — it's because people are counting on you. Your health, your strength, your faithfulness have downstream effects. Children, clients, friends, family — they need you to show up strong. Be courageous because there's a purpose bigger than yourself at stake." },
    { v:"I have fought the good fight, I have finished the race, and I have remained faithful.", r:"2 Timothy 4:7", d:"He fought well. He finished. He remained faithful. These three things are Paul's summary of his entire life. Not most impressive results. Not best metrics. These three. This is worth building toward. The life that can say at the end — I fought well and I did not quit." },
    { v:"And now the prize awaits me — the crown of righteousness, which the Lord, the righteous Judge, will give me.", r:"2 Timothy 4:8", d:"The prize awaits. It's not yet received — but it is certain. The confidence of this hope shapes how you run. You run knowing there's something worth running toward. Let the prize reshape the pace you set and the perseverance you bring today." },
    { v:"I discipline my body like an athlete, training it to do what it should.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:27", d:"Training the body like an athlete — deliberately, intentionally, with purpose. Paul didn't coast. He trained his body with intent to align it with the life he was called to live. You are doing the same thing every time you show up and choose the hard right thing. This is not just physical — it is the formation of a person." },
    { v:"So I run with purpose in every step. I am not just shadowboxing.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:26", d:"Run with purpose in every step. Not going through the motions. Not just filling time. Every session has an intention. Every rep has a reason. This is what separates training that transforms from activity that merely passes time. Know why you're doing what you're doing. Run with purpose." },
    { v:"Wait patiently for the Lord. Be brave and courageous. Yes, wait patiently for the Lord.", r:"Psalm 27:14", d:"Brave and courageous in the waiting. The world rewards urgency. Waiting with faith — trusting that what's invisible is still growing — is one of the bravest things you can do. The repetition in this verse is not an accident. The waiting is the brave thing. Stay in it." },
    { v:"What shall we say? If God is for us, who can ever be against us?", r:"Romans 8:31", d:"If God is for you — settled fact — then what can actually stand against you? The scale? The comparison? The voice that says you're not enough? None of these can prevail against the God who is actively, personally for you. Stand on that when the hard thing is hard." },
    { v:"The Lord your God is in your midst, a mighty one who will save.", r:"Zephaniah 3:17", d:"He takes delight in you and rejoices over you with gladness and singing. Not tolerates you. Not monitors your progress. Rejoices. The God who fights on your behalf also celebrates you. You are not a burden to him. Train with the knowledge that the One watching your effort is not a critic. He is a Father who delights in seeing you try." },
    { v:"Be strong and courageous! Do not be frightened, and do not be dismayed, for the Lord your God is with you wherever you go.", r:"Joshua 1:9", d:"Courage is a daily choice. The same command comes again because courage is not a one-time decision. It's chosen today. And tomorrow. Each choice makes the next one slightly easier. Choose courage today." },
  ],
  6: [
    { v:"Let us run with endurance the race God has set before us.", r:"Hebrews 12:1", d:"The race God set before you is specifically yours — not someone else's. Comparison is one of the fastest ways to lose your race, because it causes you to run someone else's. Strip off every weight — including the weight of measuring yourself against others — and run the race marked out for you. With endurance. Not sprinting, not coasting. Enduring." },
    { v:"We do this by keeping our eyes on Jesus, the champion who initiates and perfects our faith.", r:"Hebrews 12:2", d:"Eyes on Jesus — not on the competition, not on the mirror, not on the metrics. He initiates and perfects your faith. He started it and he will complete it. In the long middle of the race where nothing dramatic is happening — fix your eyes on the champion who ran his own race to completion." },
    { v:"Think of all the hostility he endured from sinful people; then you won't become weary and give up.", r:"Hebrews 12:3", d:"Think of what he endured — not to shame yourself, but to gain perspective. He endured hostility, rejection, suffering, and death. And he didn't quit. When you're tempted to give up because this is hard, because results aren't there, because motivation has evaporated — think of him. Then take the next step." },
    { v:"Don't you realize that in a race everyone runs, but only one person gets the prize? So run to win!", r:"1 Corinthians 9:24", d:"Run to win — not to participate, not to show up, not to get credit for trying. To win — to give everything you have in pursuit of the prize. Paul is talking about the wholehearted pursuit of the life you're called to. Run as if everything depends on it. Because in the formation of a life, the quality of your effort shapes the quality of your character." },
    { v:"All athletes are disciplined in their training. They do it to win a prize that will fade away, but we do it for an eternal prize.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:25", d:"Eternal prize. The athlete who trains for a trophy that will rust is more disciplined than most people. And yet what they're chasing fades. You are building toward something that doesn't fade — the character, the faithfulness, the love that outlast every physical result. Let the eternal prize motivate a deeper, more sustained discipline than any temporary reward could." },
    { v:"So I run with purpose in every step. I am not just shadowboxing.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:26", d:"Purpose in every step. Not going through motions. Not just filling hours. Every session has an intention and every rep has a reason. This is what separates training that transforms from activity that merely passes time. Know why you're doing what you're doing. Run with purpose — and that purpose will sustain you when motivation alone cannot." },
    { v:"I discipline my body like an athlete, training it to do what it should.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:27", d:"Training the body like an athlete — deliberately, with purpose, without holding back. Every time you show up, log the session, choose the hard right thing — you are doing intentional formation. Not just physical. Personal." },
    { v:"We can rejoice, too, when we run into problems and trials, for we know that they help us develop endurance.", r:"Romans 5:3", d:"Problems develop endurance — that's not a feel-good reframe, it's a description of how formation actually works. Endurance cannot be built in comfort. It builds in exactly the place you don't want to be. The hard session, the hard week, the season where you're showing up despite everything — you are in precisely the right place." },
    { v:"Patient endurance is what you need now, so that you will continue to do God's will.", r:"Hebrews 10:36", d:"Patient endurance is what you need now. Not intensity, not inspiration — patient endurance. The steady, consistent, unflashy showing up day after day. The promise attached to this is for those who endure, not for those who sprint hardest at the beginning. What you need now is to not quit." },
    { v:"So do not throw away this confident trust in the Lord. Remember the great reward it brings you!", r:"Hebrews 10:35", d:"Don't throw away the confidence. You have built something — consistency, trust, habit, faith. Don't trade it for a moment of defeat. The reward is real and it is coming. Hold the confidence. Even if you have to hold it with both hands today." },
    { v:"Blessed is the one who perseveres under trial because, having stood the test, that person will receive the crown of life.", r:"James 1:12", d:"The crown of life is given to the one who stood the test — not to the one who avoided the trial. The trial does not disqualify you. It is the very path to the crown. If you are in a hard season right now, this is not a detour. This is the road. Persevere." },
    { v:"But as for you, be strong and courageous, for your work will be rewarded.", r:"2 Chronicles 15:7", d:"Your work will be rewarded. Not some work — yours. The specific, consistent, faithful work you're doing: this session, this week, this quiet commitment when no one is watching. It is seen. It is counted. It will be rewarded. Be strong enough to keep working even when the reward is not yet visible." },
    { v:"So let's not get tired of doing what is good. At just the right time we will reap a harvest of blessing if we don't give up.", r:"Galatians 6:9", d:"Don't give up just before the harvest. The plant looks the same for weeks, and then — fruit. The body adapts on its own timeline. Character forms in the hidden places before it shows in the visible ones. Keep doing the good. The timing is not in your hands — the faithfulness is." },
    { v:"I press on to reach the end of the race and receive the heavenly prize for which God is calling us.", r:"Philippians 3:14", d:"Press on — lean forward into the race with full weight toward the finish. Not jogging. Not drifting. Pressing. This is how you run the long middle — not with the excitement of the start, but with the determined lean of someone who knows the finish line is real and the prize is worth the press." },
    { v:"I have fought the good fight, I have finished the race, and I have remained faithful.", r:"2 Timothy 4:7", d:"Three things Paul left as his summary. He fought — real resistance, real difficulty. He finished — the most important thing about a race is whether you finish, not how fast you started. He remained faithful. Not the most impressive resume. Just these three." },
    { v:"And now the prize awaits me — the crown of righteousness.", r:"2 Timothy 4:8", d:"The prize is already in place — being held for the one who finishes. Paul's confidence is not in his own goodness but in the righteousness of the Judge. He gives the crown to those who loved his appearing — who lived in hopeful anticipation of what's coming. Let that hope shape how you run today." },
    { v:"Work willingly at whatever you do, as though you were working for the Lord rather than for people.", r:"Colossians 3:23", d:"Strict training — not casual, not when convenient. Paul saw the serious athlete and said: this is the model for the spiritual life. The spiritual life deserves at least as much dedication as athletic training. Your training today is practice in the kind of disciplined seriousness that shapes a person capable of running all the way to the finish." },
    { v:"Remember that the Lord will give you an inheritance as your reward, and that the Master you are serving is Christ.", r:"Colossians 3:24", d:"The development of endurance is a present-tense process — happening right now. The hard thing you're in is not a setback from the development. It is the mechanism of the development. Rejoice — not because it's easy, but because you can see what is being built in it." },
    { v:"But the one who endures to the end will be saved.", r:"Matthew 10:22", d:"At just the right time — God's timing, not yours. The harvest comes when the crop is ready. The risk in consistent practice is the weariness that precedes the breakthrough. Don't give up just before the harvest. Keep doing the good. The faithfulness is in your hands. The timing is not." },
    { v:"Remain faithful even when facing death, and I will give you the crown of life.", r:"Revelation 2:10", d:"Faithful when it costs. Not faithful when convenient, when results are obvious, when everyone is watching. Faithful when it costs something real — comfort, ease, immediate gratification. The crown of life is not for those who were faithful when it was easy. It is for those who held on when they had every reason to let go." },
    { v:"I have told you all this so that you may have peace in me. Take heart, because I have overcome the world.", r:"John 16:33", d:"According to their deeds — what you actually do today will be counted. Not your intentions, not your feelings. Your actual deeds. Every genuine act of faithfulness, every session completed, every choice that honors God with your body — these are being seen, counted, and will be rewarded." },
    { v:"In the same way, let your good deeds shine out for all to see, so that everyone will praise your heavenly Father.", r:"Matthew 5:16", d:"Walk through. Not sprint past, not teleport past. Walk through. The valley has a path through it, and God walks it with you. The hard season, the painful struggle — God is close beside you in it. Not watching from a distance. Beside you. That changes what the valley is capable of taking from you." },
    { v:"We are pressed on every side by troubles, but we are not crushed. We get knocked down, but we are not destroyed.", r:"2 Corinthians 4:8–9", d:"When you're tempted to give up, look at what Jesus endured — not to shame yourself, but to gain perspective. He endured hostility, rejection, suffering, and death. And he didn't quit. Whatever you're enduring today is survivable. Think of him. Then take the next step." },
    { v:"Those who trust in the Lord will find new strength. They will soar high on wings like eagles. They will run and not grow weary.", r:"Isaiah 40:31", d:"Put on the armor of right living — chosen, equipped, worn intentionally. Every morning is a chance to put it on again: the decision to honor your body, to train with integrity, to live as someone who belongs to the light. The night of old habits is passing. Put on the new day." },
    { v:"For our struggle is not against flesh and blood, but against the rulers, against the powers of this dark world.", r:"Ephesians 6:12", d:"The deeds that shine are the consistent ones — the daily faithfulness that accumulates into something visible over time. Your training is one of those deeds. The health you steward, the energy you bring because you've invested in your body — these shine. People notice. And it points to something bigger than you." },
    { v:"I will keep on hoping for your help; I will praise you more and more.", r:"Psalm 71:14", d:"Continue. God's will is not a destination to reach — it's a road to walk. Keep going. Not to arrive faster. Not to be more impressive. To continue. The receiving of what's been promised follows the continuing. Stay on the road." },
    { v:"I can do everything through Christ, who gives me strength.", r:"Philippians 4:13", d:"Pressed but not crushed. The long middle of the race is where this verse lives — where trouble presses from all sides and clarity is hard to find. The promise is: not crushed. Not despairing. There is a floor beneath you even in the hardest middle. You are held. Keep going." },
    { v:"Even when I walk through the darkest valley, I will not be afraid, for you are close beside me.", r:"Psalm 23:4", d:"Soar, then run, then walk. The promise includes all three speeds — the extraordinary moments and the ordinary ones. The soaring is exhilarating. But the walking-without-fainting is just as miraculous. The grace to show up on an ordinary day and do ordinary work without quitting — this is the endurance being promised." },
    { v:"Seek the Kingdom of God above all else, and live righteously, and he will give you everything you need.", r:"Matthew 6:33", d:"The real battle is not against the weight on the bar or the number on the scale. It's against the forces that tell you to quit, that tell you your body is your enemy, that tell you you're not worth the effort. The spiritual battle for how you see yourself is real and it matters." },
    { v:"Patient endurance is what you need now, so that you will continue to do God's will. Then you will receive all that he has promised.", r:"Hebrews 10:36", d:"Keep on hoping. Hope is not a one-time decision — it's the choice you make again and again, in every ordinary day, when circumstances aren't cooperating. Praise that increases — that doubles and redoubles — is the response of someone who has found that hope held. Let your praise grow in proportion to what God has sustained you through." },
  ],
  7: [
    { v:"So if the Son sets you free, you are truly free.", r:"John 8:36", d:"Truly free — not partially free. The freedom Jesus offers is liberation of the interior person from shame, performance anxiety, the exhausting project of earning your own worth. You are free. Train from that freedom. Rest from that freedom. Live from it." },
    { v:"You have been called to live in freedom. Use your freedom to serve one another in love.", r:"Galatians 5:13", d:"Freedom for service. The energy once spent on self-condemnation, on anxious management of your own image — that energy is freed up for love. You are free. Use the freedom to serve. Let the health you're building be poured out for the people God has placed in your life." },
    { v:"And you will know the truth, and the truth will set you free.", r:"John 8:32", d:"Truth sets free. The truth about your body — that it is fearfully and wonderfully made, a temple of the Spirit, a gift and not a problem — genuinely known, produces freedom. Freedom from the comparison trap. Freedom from the shame cycle. Freedom to steward what you've been given without contempt." },
    { v:"Wherever the Spirit of the Lord is, there is freedom.", r:"2 Corinthians 3:17", d:"Wherever the Spirit is, freedom shows up. Invite the Spirit into your training, into the discipline and the rest, into the way you think about your body and your progress. Freedom is not a spiritual state you achieve — it is a presence you receive." },
    { v:"Many are the plans in a person's heart, but it is the Lord's purpose that prevails.", r:"Proverbs 19:21", d:"You are allowed to plan. God doesn't dismiss your goals. But the deeper truth is that God's purpose is what endures. When your plans align with his purpose, they have a solidity that human ambition alone can't provide. Hold your plans humbly. Ask God to align them with his purpose." },
    { v:"The Lord will work out his plans for my life — for your faithful love, O Lord, endures forever.", r:"Psalm 138:8", d:"He is working it out — right now. In the season that makes sense and the season that doesn't. In the progress you can see and the growth you cannot yet measure. The faithful love driving his plans never ends. He hasn't paused. He hasn't given up on you." },
    { v:"You didn't choose me. I chose you. I appointed you to go and produce lasting fruit.", r:"John 15:16", d:"You were appointed to something. Your health, your strength, your capacity — these are part of your equipment for the assignment. The fruit you're meant to produce is lasting — not the fruit of a single impressive session, but the sustained fruit of a life lived consistently in purpose." },
    { v:"For we are his workmanship, created in Christ Jesus for good works, which God prepared beforehand.", r:"Ephesians 2:10", d:"Walk in them. The good works were prepared in advance — not something you have to invent. Your job is to be present and capable for the walking. The health you're building is what you need for the walk ahead. Train to be ready." },
    { v:"If God is for us, who can ever be against us?", r:"Romans 8:31", d:"Since God is for you — since it is settled fact — what can stand against you? The scale? The comparison? The voice of shame? None of these can prevail against the God who is actively, personally for you. Stand in that. Train in that." },
    { v:"Since he did not spare even his own Son but gave him up for us all, won't he also give us everything else?", r:"Romans 8:32", d:"He gave the most costly thing he had. That means the lesser things — the strength, the energy, the clarity — are not beyond his willingness to give. The cross proves he's not stingy. Ask for what you need." },
    { v:"I am the vine; you are the branches. Those who remain in me, and I in them, will produce much fruit.", r:"John 15:5", d:"Remain. Stay connected. The branch that disconnects from the vine withers regardless of how much effort it exerts independently. The fruit of your training — the health, the strength, the discipline — grows from connection to Christ, not from straining alone. Remain in him. The fruit will come." },
    { v:"But if you remain in me and my words remain in you, you may ask for anything you want, and it will be granted!", r:"John 15:7", d:"When you remain in him and his words remain in you — your desires are shaped by his. What you ask for begins to align with what is good and true. The desires formed in genuine abiding are the ones that can be asked for freely. Remain. Let his words form your desires." },
    { v:"What does the Lord require of you? To act justly and to love mercy and to walk humbly with your God.", r:"Micah 6:8", d:"Walk humbly. Not sprint impressively. Not perform magnificently. Walk. Humbly. With God. The Christian life is fundamentally a walking — a steady, sustained, everyday journey in company with God. Your training supports that walking. It gives you the energy and embodied health to stay present to what is required of you each day." },
    { v:"Love the Lord your God with all your heart and with all your soul and with all your mind.", r:"Matthew 22:37", d:"All of yourself — your heart, your soul, your mind, your strength. Training is one avenue of loving God with all. When you train as an act of love, the motivation shifts. You're not trying to control an unruly body. You're offering your whole self to the God who deserves all of it." },
    { v:"Love your neighbor as yourself.", r:"Matthew 22:39", d:"Apart from him you can do nothing — and this is a liberation, not a discouragement. You are not meant to sustain yourself by yourself. The pressure of self-sufficiency is lifted. Abide in Christ, and the capacity for fruit comes with the abiding. The effort is still yours to give. The source is his to be." },
    { v:"For apart from me you can do nothing.", r:"John 15:5", d:"Generously provides — not exactly enough, but generously, with surplus for sharing. You are being resourced for more than yourself. The strength, the health, the energy you're building has overflow for others. Let that reframe the training: you are building something that can overflow." },
    { v:"God will generously provide all you need. Then you will always have everything you need and plenty left over to share with others.", r:"2 Corinthians 9:8", d:"I know the one in whom I trust — person-based trust, not outcome-based. You trust Christ: who he is, what he has done, what he has promised. Hand over your body, your goals, your progress, your timeline. He can guard what you entrust. Trust the Keeper with the thing you care about most." },
    { v:"For I know the one in whom I trust, and I am sure that he is able to guard what I have entrusted to him.", r:"2 Timothy 1:12", d:"When you serve the least — the overlooked, the vulnerable — you serve Christ. This reframes what you're building strength for. When your health gives you the capacity to show up for someone who needs you, you are serving the King himself. Train for the people who need you to show up whole." },
    { v:"The Lord himself goes before you and will be with you; he will never leave you nor forsake you.", r:"Deuteronomy 31:8", d:"He will never leave you. Whatever you step into — the hard training season, the uncertain health journey, the gap between who you are and who you're becoming — you are not stepping into it alone. He goes before. He stays beside. The path ahead has already been walked by someone who will not leave." },
    { v:"Glory to God in highest heaven, and peace on earth to those with whom God is pleased.", r:"Luke 2:14", d:"Personally — God's presence is not delegated. He goes personally before you. You are known, and the One who knows you goes ahead of you into whatever comes next. Don't be afraid. He has already been there." },
    { v:"When you did it to one of the least of these my brothers and sisters, you were doing it to me.", r:"Matthew 25:40", d:"As yourself — the love of neighbor requires a baseline of healthy self-regard. The kind of care for yourself that makes genuine care for others possible. Care for yourself as you would want to care for the person you love most. Then pour that overflow into them." },
    { v:"Live as people who are free, not using your freedom as a cover-up for evil, but living as servants of God.", r:"1 Peter 2:16", d:"Called — intentionally, specifically, personally. Before you earned it, before you deserved it, this was his plan. You are walking in a purpose older than you are. Let that settle the question of whether you belong here, whether you're doing enough, whether it's worth it." },
    { v:"I am leaving you with a gift — peace of mind and heart. The peace I give is a gift the world cannot give.", r:"John 14:27", d:"God knit you together — stitch by specific stitch, cell by cell, with care and intention. The particular way you're put together: the way you learn, the way you move, your specific strengths and limitations — all of it was knit. Not assembled randomly. Knit. By hand. With care. Honor the intricate work." },
    { v:"Whatever you do or say, do it as a representative of the Lord Jesus, giving thanks through him to God the Father.", r:"Colossians 3:17", d:"Put the first thing first. When God is genuinely first — when the kingdom is sought above training goals, above appearance — everything else finds its proper place. The training, the nutrition, the rest — when these serve the kingdom rather than replacing it, they become sustainable and life-giving." },
    { v:"Work willingly at whatever you do, as though you were working for the Lord rather than for people.", r:"Colossians 3:23", d:"For the Lord — not for the mirror, not for the scale, not for the approval of others. When you work as though the Lord is watching — because he is — the standard shifts. Not to performance anxiety but to genuine excellence offered as worship. Bring all of yourself today. For him." },
    { v:"God saved us and called us to live a holy life — not because we deserved it, but because that was his plan.", r:"2 Timothy 1:9", d:"A representative of the Lord Jesus. Everything you do — how you train, how you speak about your body, how you treat yourself and others — you carry his name. Let every session be something you'd be glad to carry his name into." },
    { v:"You made all the delicate, inner parts of my body and knit me together in my mother's womb.", r:"Psalm 139:13", d:"Glory and peace — both at once. When your life is ordered in a way that reflects God's goodness — when your health, your strength, your choices point to something larger than self — glory happens. Train for the glory of God. Let it be the thing your whole life is aimed at." },
    { v:"Seek the Kingdom of God above all else, and live righteously, and he will give you everything you need.", r:"Matthew 6:33", d:"Freedom, not rule-following, is what drives sustainable change. The energy once spent managing shame is freed up for love. Use the freedom you have been given for something worth giving it to." },
    { v:"For this is how God loved the world: He gave his one and only Son, so that everyone who believes in him will not perish but have eternal life.", r:"John 3:16", d:"He goes before and stays behind. Before you — into whatever comes next. Behind you — covering everything that has passed. And his hand of blessing is on your head in the present. You are going into the future preceded and followed by God, with his hand on you right now." },
    { v:"So be strong and courageous! Do not be afraid and do not panic. For the Lord your God will personally go ahead of you.", r:"Deuteronomy 31:6", d:"Do not be afraid — said again, because the need to say it doesn't go away. Courage is renewed daily. You choose it again today. He is personally going before you. Fear gives way to that knowledge." },
    { v:"I am the vine; you are the branches. Those who remain in me will produce much fruit. For apart from me you can do nothing.", r:"John 15:5", d:"I am the vine — this isn't a suggestion about best practices. It's a description of how life actually flows. You are a branch. Branches do not manufacture fruit. They receive it from the vine. Remain in him. That's the whole instruction. Everything else follows from remaining." },
  ],
  8: [
    { v:"Don't you realize that your body is the temple of the Holy Spirit, who lives in you and was given to you by God? You do not belong to yourself.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:19", d:"Temple — not a machine, not a project, not a problem to be solved. A temple: the place where the presence of God dwells. That's what Paul calls your body. Every time you train, you are tending the place where God has chosen to live. Every time you rest, you are honoring his dwelling. Take care of this place. It belongs to him." },
    { v:"For God bought you with a high price. So you must honor God with your body.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:20", d:"High price — the language of costly purchase. You were bought at the cost of the Son of God. That transaction changes your relationship with your body. It's not fully yours to do with as you please. It belongs to the One who paid for it. Honoring God with your body is the appropriate response to being purchased at infinite cost." },
    { v:"So whether you eat or drink, or whatever you do, do it all for the glory of God.", r:"1 Corinthians 10:31", d:"Whatever you do — including the session that feels ordinary, the meal that's unremarkable, the sleep that seems too mundane to matter. All of it is territory for glory. Not by making it grandiose. By making it intentional and offered. The mundane choices are opportunities for worship." },
    { v:"Dear friend, I hope all is well with you and that you are as healthy in body as you are strong in spirit.", r:"3 John 1:2", d:"John's prayer connects physical health and spiritual strength. These are not separate domains. The body and spirit are partners in a whole person. The same intentionality you bring to your spiritual life belongs in the care of your body. Both can flourish together." },
    { v:"Physical training is good, but training for godliness is much better, promising benefits in this life and in the life to come.", r:"1 Timothy 4:8", d:"Physical training is called good — not dismissed, not deprioritized. Good. And training for godliness is better, not because the body doesn't matter, but because character has a longer return. Build both. Let physical training serve the broader formation. Let every session be an exercise in discipline, patience, and perseverance that shapes you spiritually as much as physically." },
    { v:"So let the Holy Spirit guide your lives. Then you won't be doing what your sinful nature craves.", r:"Galatians 5:16", d:"Spirit-led choices about your body look like honoring what it needs, not just what it craves. Resting when it needs rest. Moving when it needs movement. The Holy Spirit is not confined to obvious spiritual activities. He leads in the kitchen, in the gym, in the choice to go to bed on time." },
    { v:"Give your bodies to God because of all he has done for you. Let them be a living and holy sacrifice — the kind he will find acceptable.", r:"Romans 12:1", d:"A living sacrifice — not dead on an altar, but alive, active, and offered. Daily life as worship. You offer your body — not just in religious activities, but in every session, every meal, every decision about rest and recovery. The offering is daily and embodied. Your body is the sacrifice. Give it." },
    { v:"Don't let the world around you squeeze you into its own mold, but let God re-make you so that your whole attitude of mind is changed.", r:"Romans 12:2", d:"One whole body — integrated, each part serving the others. Neglecting mobility affects strength. Neglecting sleep affects recovery. Neglecting nutrition affects energy. The body is designed for wholeness. Train the whole person, not just the impressive parts." },
    { v:"The human body has many parts, but the many parts make up one whole body.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:12", d:"The less visible parts of your training — the deep stabilizers no one sees, the recovery work, the sleep, the small muscles that keep joints healthy — these are actually the most necessary. Don't skip the things that seem minor. They may be doing the most important work." },
    { v:"God has put each part just where he wants it.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:18", d:"God placed each part just where he wanted it. Your body — in its specific configuration, with its particular strengths and limitations — is placed by God. The limitation that frustrates you may be the very thing that shapes your character. The weakness that humbles you may be where his power is most evident." },
    { v:"Some parts of the body that seem weakest and least important are actually the most necessary.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:22", d:"Marvelous. That's the word for what you are — not for what you could become, not for what you look like when everything is going well. But for what you already are, as you are. God's response to his own craftsmanship in you is 'marvelous.' Receive that. Let it change how you show up to train." },
    { v:"All of you together are Christ's body, and each of you is a part of it.", r:"1 Corinthians 12:27", d:"Energetic, strong, a hard worker — this is the description of the woman who fears God. Not primarily aesthetic but functional. She has the energy and strength to do what she's called to do. This is the purpose of physical training: not appearance but capability. Build the energy and strength to be the person God has called you to be." },
    { v:"I praise you because I am fearfully and wonderfully made; your works are wonderful, I know that full well.", r:"Psalm 139:14", d:"Want without work produces nothing. Work without desire is unsustainable. But desire aligned with hard work produces prosperity — the deep kind: health, capability, the quiet satisfaction of becoming who you intended to be. The desires of your heart are worth working for." },
    { v:"She is energetic and strong, a hard worker.", r:"Proverbs 31:17", d:"Mere talk. The conversation about wanting to be healthier. The planning without acting. The intentions without sessions. All of it is talk until you actually show up and do the work. The profit is in the work itself. Show up. The talking is only the beginning." },
    { v:"She watches over the affairs of her household and does not eat the bread of idleness.", r:"Proverbs 31:27", d:"A peaceful heart produces a healthy body — this is not just metaphor, the research confirms it. Anxiety, cortisol, the slow corrosion of comparison and self-contempt — these have physical effects. What is the state of your interior today? The peace you cultivate inwardly will show in the body over time." },
    { v:"Lazy people want much but get little, but those who work hard will prosper.", r:"Proverbs 13:4", d:"Kind words are healthy — including the words you speak to yourself. The internal monologue about your body, your progress, your limitations is not neutral. The harshness you speak inward produces something. What would it look like to speak to yourself with the same kindness you would offer someone you love?" },
    { v:"Work brings profit, but mere talk leads to poverty!", r:"Proverbs 14:23", d:"You reap what you sow — a physical law applied spiritually, and also just a physical law. The body operates by the same principle. Consistent sowing — of good sleep, wise nutrition, faithful training — eventually produces a harvest. You can't short-circuit the process. But you also can't consistently sow faithfulness and receive nothing." },
    { v:"Whatever you do, work at it with all your heart, as working for the Lord, not for human masters.", r:"Colossians 3:23", d:"Living to please the Spirit in your body looks like honoring what it needs, not just what it craves. The harvest of living this way is actual life — not just physical longevity but the quality of aliveness that comes from a body honored and a Spirit followed. Sow to life today." },
    { v:"A peaceful heart leads to a healthy body; jealousy is like cancer in the bones.", r:"Proverbs 14:30", d:"God nurses and restores. When injury comes, when illness comes, when the body won't cooperate — God is not absent from the process. He nurses. He restores. Healing is not always immediate or complete in the way you want. But the God who attends to your body's struggles is still at work." },
    { v:"Kind words are like honey — sweet to the soul and healthy for the body.", r:"Proverbs 16:24", d:"He heals the brokenhearted and bandages their wounds — physical and otherwise. God's healing attention includes the body: the torn muscle, the chronic issue, the injury that won't resolve. He is the One who bandages — not impersonally, but with the care of a healer who knows exactly where the wound is." },
    { v:"Don't be deceived: God cannot be mocked. A man reaps what he sows.", r:"Galatians 6:7", d:"The Spirit leads in all of it — including the choices about your body that seem purely practical. What to eat. When to rest. How to move. The Spirit is not confined to the obviously spiritual. Invite him into the ordinary, embodied decisions of daily life." },
    { v:"Those who live to please the Spirit will harvest everlasting life.", r:"Galatians 6:8", d:"All athletes are disciplined — they do it for a prize that will fade. You are doing it for an eternal prize. Let the eternal prize — the character being built, the faithfulness being established — motivate a deeper and more sustained discipline than any temporary reward could produce." },
    { v:"The Lord nurses them when they are sick and restores them to health.", r:"Psalm 41:3", d:"The body is a temple — this truth is worth returning to repeatedly, especially in a culture that either worships the body or dismisses it. It is neither an idol nor irrelevant. It is a temple: sacred, worth tending, the dwelling of the Spirit. Honor it accordingly." },
    { v:"He heals the brokenhearted and bandages their wounds.", r:"Psalm 147:3", d:"Do not eat the bread of idleness in the domain of your health. Not frantic, not obsessive — but consistently active. The woman of Proverbs 31 tends her household daily, not heroically. The daily tending is the thing. Show up consistently. The heroic moments are built on ordinary faithfulness." },
    { v:"I discipline my body like an athlete, training it to do what it should.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:27", d:"An eternal prize — not a temporary trophy. The discipline you build in your body spills into your character. The consistency you learn in physical training shows up in your relationships and your faithfulness. Train the temple with that long view in mind." },
    { v:"And I will put a new spirit in you. I will take out your stony, stubborn heart and give you a tender, responsive heart.", r:"Ezekiel 36:26", d:"A new heart — responsive, tender, alive — is what God gives when the stony, stubborn heart is surrendered. You cannot manufacture the new heart. You receive it. And from it, the new habits, the new responses, the new relationship with your body become possible. Ask for the new heart first." },
    { v:"All athletes are disciplined in their training. They do it to win a prize that will fade away, but we do it for an eternal prize.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:25", d:"The discipline of the athlete applied to the temple of the Spirit. Physical training is not the end — it serves something larger. The discipline you build in your body formation spills into your character formation. Let every session be part of that larger project." },
    { v:"We are being transformed into his image with ever-increasing glory.", r:"2 Corinthians 3:18", d:"Transformed into his image — the whole person, cared for with the whole attention. Your body is part of this transformation, not just your soul. The entire person, stewarded faithfully, is being formed into something that increasingly reflects the image of God. This is the ultimate goal of all stewardship." },
    { v:"Do you not know that your body is the temple of the Holy Spirit? Therefore honor God with your body.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:19", d:"Because you belong to him — that's the foundation. Everything else flows from that belonging. You are not trying to make yourself belong. You already belong. Train from that." },
    { v:"So let the Holy Spirit guide your lives.", r:"Galatians 5:16", d:"The Spirit guides your life — all of it, not just the officially spiritual parts. Follow the Spirit's leading into the ordinary choices about your body today. What does the body need? What serves life? That kind of discernment is available. Ask for it." },
    { v:"For God bought you with a high price. So you must honor God with your body.", r:"1 Corinthians 6:20", d:"For God bought you with a high price — not abstract theology, but a foundation for every practical decision about your body. How you eat, sleep, train, and rest are all responses to this purchase. The cost was infinite. The response is a life that honors what was paid." },
  ],
  9: [
    { v:"For God has not given us a spirit of fear and timidity, but of power, love, and self-discipline.", r:"2 Timothy 1:7", d:"Power, love, self-discipline — three gifts given together by the Spirit. The self-discipline described here is not the grim, white-knuckled effort of someone barely holding on. It flows from the same source as power and love. It is a gift, not a product of willpower alone. Ask for it. Then act from the asking." },
    { v:"I discipline my body like an athlete, training it to do what it should.", r:"1 Corinthians 9:27", d:"Paul took the possibility of disqualification seriously. The message he carried could be undermined by the life he lived. The same is true for you. Your private discipline — the session no one sees, the choice no one knows about — either aligns with or contradicts who you say you are. Train the person you are becoming, not just the body you're building." },
    { v:"No discipline is enjoyable while it is happening — it's painful! But afterward there will be a peaceful harvest of right living.", r:"Hebrews 12:11", d:"The afterward. The harvest. There is a peaceful harvest of right living that comes from sustained discipline — but it comes afterward. Not during. The discipline is painful when it's happening. The author doesn't minimize that. He just points to what follows. Stay in it. The afterward is worth it." },
    { v:"For the Lord corrects those he loves, just as a father corrects a child in whom he delights.", r:"Proverbs 3:12", d:"Discipline from a loving God looks different from punishment from an indifferent authority. It's targeted, purposeful, motivated by love. When something needs to change — when progress stalls, when patterns need addressing — receive it as correction from a Father, not condemnation from a judge." },
    { v:"Don't reject the Lord's discipline, and don't be upset when he corrects you.", r:"Proverbs 3:11", d:"Don't reject the discipline. The temptation is to get defensive, to minimize, to explain away what God is correcting. The path forward is through, not around. Receive the correction. The Lord corrects those he loves — which means correction is evidence of his care, not his disappointment." },
    { v:"Look straight ahead, and fix your eyes on what lies before you.", r:"Proverbs 4:25", d:"Look straight ahead. Not sideways at what someone else is doing. Not backward. Straight ahead — at the next step, the next rep, the next faithful decision. Peripheral comparison is one of the fastest ways to lose the road. Fix your eyes on what lies before you. Just the next step." },
    { v:"Mark out a straight path for your feet; stay on the safe path.", r:"Proverbs 4:26", d:"Mark out the path — deliberate, intentional, not wandering and hoping. You need to know where you're going and how you plan to get there. The training program is the path. Once marked, stay on it. The safest path is the one you can see clearly and walk intentionally." },
    { v:"Don't get sidetracked; keep your feet from following evil.", r:"Proverbs 4:27", d:"Don't get sidetracked. The distractions are rarely dramatic — they're small deviations that accumulate. One skipped session becomes two. One compromised meal becomes a pattern. The subtle drift is more dangerous than the obvious detour. Stay on the path." },
    { v:"We capture their rebellious thoughts and teach them to obey Christ.", r:"2 Corinthians 10:5", d:"Capture the rebellious thoughts. The thoughts about your body that run unchecked — comparison, shame, contempt — can be captured and redirected. They don't have to run free. Every time you replace a lie with truth, you are doing real spiritual work." },
    { v:"Fix your thoughts on what is true, and honorable, and right, and pure, and lovely, and admirable.", r:"Philippians 4:8", d:"Fix your thoughts on what is true, honorable, right, pure, lovely, admirable — this is not positive thinking, it's truth-anchored thinking. There are true things about your body, your progress, and your God that deserve your sustained attention. Fix your thoughts there." },
    { v:"Think about things that are excellent and worthy of praise.", r:"Philippians 4:8", d:"Think about things excellent and worthy of praise. The mind is a training ground. What you rehearse there shapes who you become. This is an invitation to give your sustained attention to the things worth thinking about — starting with what God has already done in you." },
    { v:"Don't worry about anything; instead, pray about everything. Tell God what you need, and thank him for all he has done.", r:"Philippians 4:6", d:"Pray about everything instead of worrying about everything. The worry energy is real — redirect it. Every concern about your health, your progress, your body — turn it into conversation with God. The practice of praying about everything is the practice of trust, built one redirected worry at a time." },
    { v:"Then you will experience God's peace, which exceeds anything we can understand.", r:"Philippians 4:7", d:"God's peace exceeds understanding — it doesn't require favorable circumstances to operate. This is the peace available in the middle of a hard training season, a slow week, a body that won't cooperate. It is not produced by getting everything right. It is given. Ask for the guard to be posted." },
    { v:"His peace will guard your hearts and minds as you live in Christ Jesus.", r:"Philippians 4:7", d:"His peace guards your heart and mind — it stands between you and the anxiety that would otherwise invade. This is not passive: you ask for it, receive it, let it guard. The guard is already available. Position yourself to receive it." },
    { v:"So humble yourselves before God. Resist the devil, and he will flee from you.", r:"James 4:7", d:"Resist — actively push back against what opposes you. Not passive acceptance of every thought and impulse. Deliberate resistance. Push back against the voice of shame, the comparison spiral, the temptation to quit. Resist. The promise is that what opposes you will flee when you stand firm." },
    { v:"Come close to God, and God will come close to you.", r:"James 4:8", d:"Draw close — actively, deliberately. The distance between you and God is not fixed. You move toward him. He moves toward you. In the gym, on a rest day, in the middle of a hard week — draw close. Acknowledge his presence. Speak to him." },
    { v:"Humble yourselves before the Lord, and he will lift you up in honor.", r:"James 4:10", d:"He lifts up the humble — not the already-impressive, not the already-accomplished. The humble: those who know their need, who don't pretend to have it together, who acknowledge that God holds what they do not. Humility in training: accepting where you actually are instead of where you think you should be." },
    { v:"Stay alert! Watch out for your great enemy, the devil. He prowls around like a roaring lion, looking for someone to devour.", r:"1 Peter 5:8", d:"Stay alert. The spiritual life requires watchfulness — an awareness that you are in a real contest, that what you believe about yourself matters, that the voice of defeat and shame is not neutral noise. Name the voices. Resist them. They are real, but they are not all-powerful." },
    { v:"Stand firm against him, and be strong in your faith.", r:"1 Peter 5:9", d:"Stand firm. The instruction is not to run or hide — it's to stand. Remain in place under pressure. The faith you stand in is the knowledge of what is true: you are loved, you are held, God is at work, the struggle has a purpose. Stand on that." },
    { v:"After you have suffered a little while, he will restore, support, and strengthen you, and place you on a firm foundation.", r:"1 Peter 5:10", d:"After you have suffered a little while — he restores, supports, strengthens, and establishes. On the other side of the hard season. The foundation you're building — in your body and in your faith — is being made firm by the One with the longest view." },
    { v:"We should live in this evil world with wisdom, righteousness, and devotion to God.", r:"Titus 2:12", d:"Wisdom, righteousness, devotion — the framework for life in a world that offers a thousand alternatives. In the domain of your body: train wisely, choose righteously, devote the whole thing to God. All three, together, in this world." },
    { v:"Let everything you say be good and helpful, so that your words will be an encouragement to those who hear them.", r:"Ephesians 4:29", d:"Good and helpful — including what you say to yourself. The internal monologue during training, during the moments in front of the mirror — this is speech. Let it be good and helpful. Encouragement is not denial of difficulty; it is the choice to speak truthfully about what is possible." },
    { v:"Get rid of all bitterness, rage, anger, harsh words, and slander.", r:"Ephesians 4:31", d:"Get rid of bitterness — including toward yourself. The harsh internal words, the contempt for where you are — these are forms of bitterness. Get rid of them. Actively. Deliberately. Not by pretending everything is fine, but by releasing what is not serving your formation." },
    { v:"Instead, be kind to each other, tenderhearted, forgiving one another, just as God through Christ has forgiven you.", r:"Ephesians 4:32", d:"Be kind — including to yourself. The forgiveness you receive from God can be extended inward: forgiving yourself for missed sessions, poor choices, the gap between intention and action. Tenderness toward yourself is not weakness. It is the application of the gospel to your own interior life." },
    { v:"Imitate God, therefore, in everything you do, because you are his dear children.", r:"Ephesians 5:1", d:"Imitate God in everything — including how he relates to your body. God is patient with your growth. He is consistent. He pays attention to detail. He does not give up. Imitate that. Be patient with your own growth. Be consistent. Don't give up." },
    { v:"For once you were full of darkness, but now you have light from the Lord. So live as people of light!", r:"Ephesians 5:8", d:"People of light — this is who you are, not who you're trying to become. The darkness of shame, self-contempt, the belief that you're not worth caring for — that is not your home. You are a person of light. Live from that identity." },
    { v:"Warn each other every day, while it is still today, so that none of you will be deceived by sin and hardened against God.", r:"Hebrews 3:13", d:"Today. The accountability that prevents drift needs to be current — not someday, not eventually. Today is the day to tend the relationships that keep you on the right road. Stay connected. Let people speak into your life. Don't disappear." },
    { v:"Since he did not spare even his own Son, won't he also give us everything else?", r:"Romans 8:32", d:"Since he gave the most costly thing, the lesser things are not beyond his willingness to provide. The strength, the clarity, the self-control — these are not too much to ask from the God who gave his Son. Ask. The cross proves he's not stingy." },
    { v:"Teach the older men to exercise self-control, to be worthy of respect, and to live wisely.", r:"Titus 2:2", d:"Self-control worthy of respect — not harsh, but dignified. The settled self-discipline of someone who has been doing this long enough to know it's worth it. Not white-knuckling. The quiet consistency of someone who has decided. Build toward that kind of self-control." },
    { v:"Commit your actions to the Lord, and your plans will succeed.", r:"Proverbs 16:3", d:"Commit your actions to the Lord — roll them onto him. You make the plan. You do the work. You show up. And then you roll the outcome onto God rather than white-knuckling it yourself. The work is yours. The results are his. That is not an excuse for laziness — it is the posture that makes sustained effort possible." },
  ],
  10: [
    { v:"Give thanks to the Lord, for he is good! His faithful love endures forever.", r:"Psalm 107:1", d:"His faithful love endures forever — this is the reason for thanksgiving that doesn't require circumstances to go well first. The love is faithful regardless of the season, the result, the number on the scale. Gratitude rooted here is unshakeable. It doesn't depend on the good week. It depends on the unchanging character of a good God." },
    { v:"Always be joyful. Never stop praying. Be thankful in all circumstances.", r:"1 Thessalonians 5:16–18", d:"In all circumstances — the frustrating ones, the discouraging ones, the ones where progress has stalled. Not for all circumstances, as if every situation is equally desirable. In all circumstances — inside whatever is happening, choosing a posture of thanksgiving. This is a discipline. Thanksgiving in difficulty is one of the most countercultural and transformative practices available." },
    { v:"Give thanks for everything to God the Father in the name of our Lord Jesus Christ.", r:"Ephesians 5:20", d:"For everything — not just the obvious goods. The body that showed up today. The capacity to move. The breath that was there for one more rep. The rest that restored. Every ordinary good is a gift from the same God who gave the extraordinary ones." },
    { v:"Enter his gates with thanksgiving; go into his courts with praise. Give thanks to him and praise his name.", r:"Psalm 100:4", d:"Enter with thanksgiving. The posture for approaching God is gratitude, not performance. You don't earn access — you receive it, and the natural response to received grace is thanksgiving. Bring that posture into your training today: not 'I have to do this' but 'I get to do this.'" },
    { v:"For the Lord is good. His unfailing love continues forever, and his faithfulness continues to each generation.", r:"Psalm 100:5", d:"His faithfulness continues to every generation — not just to yours when you're performing well. Whatever season you're in — the abundant one or the lean one — his faithfulness is not conditional. Build your gratitude on the faithfulness, not the circumstance." },
    { v:"I will praise you, Lord, with all my heart; I will tell of all the marvelous things you have done.", r:"Psalm 9:1", d:"Tell of all the marvelous things he has done — in your body, the recovery from injury, the unexpected energy, the day you didn't think you could finish but did. Count them. Write them down. Specific praise is the most powerful kind." },
    { v:"Let all that I am praise the Lord; with my whole heart, I will praise his holy name.", r:"Psalm 103:1", d:"All that you are — including the tired parts, the frustrated parts, the parts that aren't sure the effort is working. All of it can be offered in praise. Wholehearted praise is the practice of turning the full self toward God." },
    { v:"Let all that I am praise the Lord; may I never forget the good things he does for me.", r:"Psalm 103:2", d:"Never forget the good things he does. Memory is a spiritual discipline. We forget the good things remarkably quickly and remember the hard things remarkably well. Keep a record. Write down what God has done in your body, in your life. Look at it on the days when memory fails." },
    { v:"He forgives all my sins and heals all my diseases.", r:"Psalm 103:3", d:"He forgives all sins and heals all diseases — in the same sentence. The God who addresses the soul also attends to the body. When you bring your body's struggles to God, you bring them to the One who heals. Trust the manner and timing of his healing to him." },
    { v:"He fills my life with good things. My youth is renewed like the eagle's!", r:"Psalm 103:5", d:"He fills my life with good things. My youth is renewed — not declining, not merely maintained, but renewed. This is the image of what God does with those who trust him. The energy, the capacity, the resilience you're building are God's renewing work in you. Receive that." },
    { v:"Give thanks to the Lord and proclaim his greatness. Let the whole world know what he has done.", r:"Psalm 105:1", d:"Let the whole world know what he has done. Your health journey — the struggle, the grace, the showing-up-anyway — is a testimony. Not a performance to impress, but a witness to what God does in ordinary faithfulness. Someone who is struggling needs to hear what God has done in you. Be willing to tell it." },
    { v:"I will sing to the Lord because he is good to me.", r:"Psalm 13:6", d:"I will sing to the Lord because he is good to me — the specific, personal experience of God's goodness, not just general theology. In your specific body, in your specific journey, God has been good. Find the evidence. Sing it in whatever form that takes for you." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and shield. I trust him with all my heart. He helps me, and my heart is filled with joy.", r:"Psalm 28:7", d:"He helps me and my heart is filled with joy — joy as the result of trust, not as the prerequisite for it. You trust, and the joy follows. Trust first. The joy will follow." },
    { v:"I will bless the Lord who guides me; even at night my heart instructs me.", r:"Psalm 16:7", d:"Even at night his heart instructs him. The guidance doesn't stop when you sleep. The body repairs at night. The Spirit speaks in the quiet. Rest is not the absence of God's work — it may be one of the primary times he is working. Trust the night as much as the day." },
    { v:"I know the Lord is always with me. I will not be shaken, for he is right beside me.", r:"Psalm 16:8", d:"I will not be shaken — not because nothing hard happens, but because the One beside him cannot be moved. The shakeable things: the number on the scale, the slow week, the comparison. The unshakeable thing: God right beside you. Build your stability on the unshakeable." },
    { v:"No wonder my heart is glad, and I rejoice. My body rests in safety.", r:"Psalm 16:9", d:"My body rests in safety — the whole person, body and soul, at genuine rest. Your body can rest — genuinely, not just collapse — when it is held by the One who never sleeps. Let the rest be full today. You are safe." },
    { v:"You will show me the way of life, granting me the joy of your presence and the pleasures of living with you forever.", r:"Psalm 16:11", d:"The way of life — not just existence, but fullness. The joy of God's presence is woven through the ordinary life of the body. Ask him to show you the way of life in your training, in your rest, in your health. He delights to lead." },
    { v:"Surely your goodness and unfailing love will pursue me all the days of my life.", r:"Psalm 23:6", d:"His goodness and love pursue you — actively chasing. Even on the days you feel like you're running from God, his goodness and love are following. You will be caught. The pursuit never ends." },
    { v:"I remain confident of this: I will see the goodness of the Lord in the land of the living.", r:"Psalm 27:13", d:"I will see the goodness of the Lord in the land of the living — here, now, in this life, in this body. The Psalmist has to work at this confidence. It doesn't come automatically. But he holds it. Look for the goodness of God in your body, in your recovery, in the small signs of progress. It is there to be seen." },
    { v:"Oh, how great is your goodness, which you have stored up for those who fear you.", r:"Psalm 31:19", d:"He has stored up great goodness for those who fear him. The goodness is not in short supply — it has been accumulated, ready to be poured out. The fear of the Lord here is not terror but reverent trust. Come to the stored-up goodness in reverence." },
    { v:"The Lord is good, a strong refuge when trouble comes. He is close to those who trust in him.", r:"Nahum 1:7", d:"He is close to those who trust — the nearness of God is conditioned on trust, not on perfection. When you trust God with your body — with its limitations, its progress, its healing — you draw near to the One who is close to those who trust." },
    { v:"Praise the Lord, I tell myself, and never forget the good things he does for me.", r:"Psalm 103:2", d:"Never forget — gratitude requires active maintenance. We forget the good things far too quickly. Tell yourself what God has done. Write it down. Look at the record of his faithfulness. Let the memory of what he has done be the foundation for your confidence about what he will do." },
    { v:"May the God of hope fill you completely with joy and peace because you trust in him.", r:"Romans 15:13", d:"Overflow — the hope that comes from trusting God is not just enough for you, it spills over. The joy and peace that fill you become the environment you create around you. Ask to be filled completely — so that what overflows reaches the people around you." },
    { v:"A peaceful heart leads to a healthy body.", r:"Proverbs 14:30", d:"Peace produces health — the practice of gratitude, of releasing comparison, of choosing peace over striving has a direct effect on the physical body. What is the state of your interior today? The peace you cultivate inwardly will show in the body over time." },
    { v:"Search for the Lord and for his strength; continually seek him.", r:"Psalm 105:4", d:"Continually seek him — not occasionally, not when you remember or when you need something. Continually. The seeking of God is meant to be woven into every day, every activity. Find ways to continually seek him in the ordinary. A quiet acknowledgment before you begin. A moment of gratitude after." },
    { v:"Remember the wonders he has performed, his miracles, and the rulings he has given.", r:"Psalm 105:5", d:"Remember the wonders he has performed — active, intentional recollection of what God has done in your life and in your body. The healing. The energy that arrived when you needed it. The breakthrough you didn't expect. The grace in the hard season. Remember. These are the foundations of future confidence." },
    { v:"The Lord is good to those who depend on him, to those who search for him.", r:"Lamentations 3:25", d:"He is good to those who depend on him — dependence is the key. When you stop trying to do all of this in your own strength and actually lean on God, you access a goodness you cannot manufacture. Depend. Search. Receive." },
    { v:"Taste and see that the Lord is good. Oh, the joys of those who take refuge in him!", r:"Psalm 34:8", d:"Take refuge — stop carrying everything alone, trust a strength greater than your own. The joy described here is the joy of genuine relief. The exhaustion of self-sufficiency gives way to the rest of taking refuge. Stop trying to hold everything yourself." },
    { v:"Give thanks to the Lord, for he is good! His faithful love endures forever.", r:"Psalm 118:1", d:"Give thanks to the Lord — he is good. The goodness is not circumstantial. It is character. His faithful love endures forever — not just in good seasons. Forever. Build your gratitude on what does not change." },
    { v:"Now may our Lord Jesus Christ himself and God our Father comfort you and strengthen you.", r:"2 Thessalonians 2:16–17", d:"Comfort and strengthen — both together. Comfort comes first — you are loved, held in grace. From that place, strength grows. This is the order: you are comforted first, and from the comfort, strength grows. Rest in the comfort. The strength follows." },
    { v:"The Lord is my strength and my shield. I trust him with all my heart.", r:"Psalm 28:7", d:"The Lord is my strength and shield — both offense and defense. The strength to push hard and the protection of knowing you are not exposed in your vulnerability. He is both. Trust him with the full range of what you need." },
  ],
  11: [
    { v:"Come to me, all of you who are weary and carry heavy burdens, and I will give you rest.", r:"Matthew 11:28", d:"Come to me. The invitation is to movement — but not the movement of effort. The movement of the exhausted toward the Source of rest. Jesus doesn't say 'get more efficient' or 'try harder.' He says come. If you are weary — from training, from the season, from carrying things heavier than workouts — this is the invitation. Rest is available. But you have to come to the right place for it." },
    { v:"Take my yoke upon you. Let me teach you, because I am humble and gentle at heart, and you will find rest for your souls.", r:"Matthew 11:29", d:"Gentle and humble at heart. The teacher you're learning from is not harsh. He does not berate you for not being further along. He is gentle. The yoke he offers is designed for the human frame. Take it. The learning is kind. The teacher is gentle. Find rest in that." },
    { v:"For my yoke is easy to bear, and the burden I give you is light.", r:"Matthew 11:30", d:"Easy to bear. Light. Not because nothing is asked of you, but because the weight is distributed rightly — shared with the One who walks beside you. A yoke designed for two is lighter than carrying alone. The burden that comes from following Christ is sustainable. Light. Because it is designed to be carried in partnership." },
    { v:"The Lord is my shepherd; I have all that I need. He lets me rest in green meadows.", r:"Psalm 23:1–2", d:"He lets me rest. The permission to rest comes from the shepherd — not from the completion of the to-do list, not from having done enough to deserve it. The rest is led into, not earned. The shepherd knows what the sheep needs. Receive the rest as an act of trust." },
    { v:"He leads me beside peaceful streams. He renews my strength.", r:"Psalm 23:2–3", d:"He renews my strength. The renewal comes in the leading beside still water — in the pause, the quiet, the intentional stopping. Your body grows stronger during recovery. The session tears. The rest rebuilds. Let the shepherd lead you to the still water today." },
    { v:"He guides me along right paths, bringing honor to his name.", r:"Psalm 23:3", d:"Right paths — not always easy ones. The path that brings honor to God may include the hard session, the discipline that costs, the rest that feels unproductive. Right doesn't mean comfortable. It means correctly oriented. Trust the shepherd's sense of the right path." },
    { v:"Even when I walk through the darkest valley, I will not be afraid, for you are close beside me.", r:"Psalm 23:4", d:"Even when I walk through the darkest valley — he is close beside me. Not watching from a distance. Not managing from afar. Beside. Walking with you in the hard season, the painful struggle. You are not walking through it alone. Someone who knows the valley is beside you." },
    { v:"Trust in the Lord with all your heart; do not depend on your own understanding.", r:"Proverbs 3:5", d:"Do not lean on your own understanding — not a command to stop thinking, but to hold your certainty loosely. You don't have the full picture. Seek his will. Then trust the path that appears." },
    { v:"Seek his will in all you do, and he will show you which path to take.", r:"Proverbs 3:6", d:"Seek his will in all you do — including the training decisions, the rest decisions, the nutrition choices. Ask God about your training. Ask him about what your body needs. He shows paths to those who seek. The invitation to seek is always open." },
    { v:"Then you will have healing for your body and strength for your bones.", r:"Proverbs 3:8", d:"Healing for your body and strength for your bones — the practical effects of trusting God extend into the physical. The wisdom of trusting rather than straining in your own understanding has real effects on the body — on stress levels, on recovery, on the quality of rest." },
    { v:"Give all your worries and cares to God, for he cares about you.", r:"1 Peter 5:7", d:"He cares about you — specifically, personally. Not about your category. About you. The worries about your body, your health, your progress — these are things he cares about alongside you. Cast them. God's caring is not passive. He actively attends to what you've given him." },
    { v:"Be still, and know that I am God.", r:"Psalm 46:10", d:"Be still, and know that I am God. Stillness is the posture that allows knowing. In the constant motion and noise of life, stillness is countercultural and necessary. The rest day is practice in this. Be still. Know. The order is intentional." },
    { v:"I lay down and slept, yet I woke up in safety, for the Lord was watching over me.", r:"Psalm 3:5", d:"He watches while you sleep. The recovery that happens at night — the muscle repair, the neurological consolidation — happens under God's attentive watch. You don't have to manage your recovery. You have to enter into it. Lie down. Sleep. He is watching." },
    { v:"In peace I will lie down and sleep, for you alone, O Lord, will keep me safe.", r:"Psalm 4:8", d:"In peace I will lie down and sleep — because you alone keep me safe. The act of rest is an act of trust. When you sleep, you are releasing control of your body and your world for the night. Let the sleep be full tonight. The keeping is his work." },
    { v:"He will not let you stumble; the one who watches over you will not slumber.", r:"Psalm 121:3", d:"He will not let you stumble — the One who watches over you does not slumber. God does not take breaks from watching over you. He is not distracted or asleep when the hard thing happens. He is there. And he will not let you stumble permanently — even when you do, he is already reaching to steady you." },
    { v:"The Lord himself watches over you! The Lord stands beside you as your protective shade.", r:"Psalm 121:5", d:"The Lord stands beside you as your protective shade. In a hot and relentless world — of comparison, pressure, the constant demand to be more — God's presence is shade. Shelter from the heat. A place to breathe. Allow yourself to stand in the shade today." },
    { v:"The Lord keeps you from all harm and watches over your life.", r:"Psalm 121:7", d:"He keeps you from all harm — the harm that would ultimately undo you. Not from all difficulty. Not from all struggle. But from the harm that would permanently damage what matters most. You are kept. Even in the hard thing, you are kept." },
    { v:"The Lord keeps watch over you as you come and go, both now and forever.", r:"Psalm 121:8", d:"Both now and forever. The watching never ends. God's attention to your life is not reserved for important moments. It covers the mundane, the repetitive, the ordinary day of faithful living. Both now and forever. He sees every ordinary day." },
    { v:"God gives rest to his loved ones.", r:"Psalm 127:2", d:"God gives rest to his loved ones — rest is not something you earn or schedule efficiently. It is something God gives to those he loves. The frenetic drive to optimize, to push further, to get more — when it's driven by anxiety, it misses the point. Receive the rest as a gift." },
    { v:"Don't worry about anything; instead, pray about everything.", r:"Philippians 4:6", d:"Pray instead of worry — not as a suppression technique, but as a redirection. The worry energy is real. Use it for prayer. Every concern about your body, your health, your progress — turn it into conversation with God. One redirected worry at a time is how the practice of trust is built." },
    { v:"Tell God what you need, and thank him for all he has done.", r:"Philippians 4:6", d:"Tell God what you need — not because he doesn't already know, but because the telling is an act of trust. It acknowledges dependence. Bring the thing into the light. Tell him what you actually need. Then thank him for what he has already done." },
    { v:"Then you will experience God's peace, which exceeds anything we can understand. His peace will guard your hearts and minds.", r:"Philippians 4:7", d:"Peace that exceeds understanding — it doesn't require favorable circumstances. This is the peace available in the middle of a hard training season, a slow week, a body that won't cooperate. Not produced by getting everything right. Given. Ask for the guard to be posted." },
    { v:"I am leaving you with a gift — peace of mind and heart. The peace I give is a gift the world cannot give.", r:"John 14:27", d:"A gift the world cannot give. Christ's peace holds in conditions where the world's peace collapses. When the results aren't there, when the hard thing is hard, when the season is long and dry — the gift of peace is still available. It was given at the cross. Receive it." },
    { v:"Cast your cares on the Lord and he will sustain you; he will never let the righteous be shaken.", r:"Psalm 55:22", d:"He will sustain you — not just manage, not just maintain. Sustain: nourish, hold, keep going. Cast what you're carrying. Don't try to carry it yourself into the gym, into your day, into your relationships. He sustains those who trust him with what they're carrying." },
    { v:"When doubts filled my mind, your comfort gave me renewed hope and cheer.", r:"Psalm 94:19", d:"When doubts filled my mind, your comfort gave me renewed hope and cheer. Doubt and hope can coexist. God's comfort is available in the middle of the doubt — not to silence it with false certainty, but to give renewed hope that holds anyway." },
    { v:"The Lord is close to the brokenhearted; he rescues those whose spirits are crushed.", r:"Psalm 34:18", d:"Close to the brokenhearted — not at a distance from them. Close. When the spirit is crushed — by slow progress, by the return of old habits, by the gap between who you are and who you wanted to be — this is where God is most near. Crushed spirits are places of particular divine attention." },
    { v:"He heals the brokenhearted and bandages their wounds.", r:"Psalm 147:3", d:"He bandages their wounds — tender, specific, attentive to the actual wound that is there. Not a general wellness solution. Attentive, specific care. Bring your specific wounds — physical, emotional — to the God who bandages. He is close enough to bandage." },
    { v:"Morning, noon, and night I cry out in my distress, and the Lord hears my voice.", r:"Psalm 55:17", d:"I will call on God, and the Lord will rescue me. The rescue is available, but calling is the first step. In seasons of weariness, the smallest act of faith is calling out. 'Help.' 'I need you.' 'I don't know how to keep going.' These are prayers. He hears them." },
    { v:"Come close to God, and God will come close to you.", r:"James 4:8", d:"Morning, noon, and night — the distress is persistent, and so is the calling. God hears at all three times, without impatience, without wearing out. The prayer that comes from genuine distress is not an annoyance to God. It is a direct line to the One who hears every time." },
    { v:"In peace I will lie down and sleep, for you alone, O Lord, will keep me safe.", r:"Psalm 4:8", d:"The movement is mutual. You draw close; he draws close. In the middle of a recovery day, a quiet rest, a slow moment — draw close. Acknowledge his presence. Speak to him. He is coming close to those who come close. You are never far from the nearness you are seeking." },
  ],
  12: [
    { v:"Your word is a lamp to guide my feet and a light for my path.", r:"Psalm 119:105", d:"A lamp for the next step — not a spotlight on the whole road. You don't need to see the entire journey from here to your goal. You need enough light for today. What is the next faithful step? The next session. The next meal. The next rest. Walk in the light you have." },
    { v:"The Lord is my light and my salvation — so why should I be afraid?", r:"Psalm 27:1", d:"Light and salvation from the same source. In seasons where it's hard to see what is working or where you're going — the Lord is the light. Not a feeling, not a result. The Lord himself. Why should you be afraid? You have what you need to take the next step." },
    { v:"In the same way, let your good deeds shine out for all to see, so that everyone will praise your heavenly Father.", r:"Matthew 5:16", d:"Let your good deeds shine — not the dramatic moments, but the consistent faithfulness that accumulates over time. The person who kept showing up, kept caring for their body, kept choosing the harder right thing — they shine. Not to draw attention to themselves. Because faithfulness is luminous." },
    { v:"You are the light of the world — like a city on a hilltop that cannot be hidden.", r:"Matthew 5:14", d:"Cannot be hidden. The light of a life genuinely lived for God becomes visible — not because you advertise it, but because it shows. Consistently. Steadily. People notice the energy, the discipline, the peace. Keep shining. Because faithfulness is its own kind of light." },
    { v:"I am the light of the world. If you follow me, you won't have to walk in darkness.", r:"John 8:12", d:"If you follow me, you won't walk in darkness. The light of Christ illuminates not just the spiritual road but the practical one — the path through training, through hard seasons, through the questions about who you're becoming. Follow him. You won't walk in darkness." },
    { v:"For everything there is a season, a time for every activity under heaven.", r:"Ecclesiastes 3:1", d:"A season for every activity. Your training has been seasonal — times of great progress and times of holding. Times of high intensity and times of necessary rest. This is not failure — it is design. Reflect on which season you've been in, and ask what the next one is calling for." },
    { v:"Yet God has made everything beautiful for its own time.", r:"Ecclesiastes 3:11", d:"Beautiful for its own time. The hard season has its beauty. The slow season has its beauty. The season of rebuilding after setback has its beauty — not because everything is pleasant, but because God makes beauty from the specific moments he places you in." },
    { v:"I know that there is nothing better for people than to be happy and to do good while they live.", r:"Ecclesiastes 3:12", d:"Do good while you live. The span of your life is the opportunity for doing good. The health you're building is not for your benefit alone — it is the resource for doing good while you have time to do it. Live well, to do good well, for as long as you have." },
    { v:"Here now is my final conclusion: Fear God and obey his commands, for this is everyone's duty.", r:"Ecclesiastes 12:13", d:"Fear God and obey his commands — the final conclusion of the wisest man who ever lived. Not the accumulation of achievement. Not the optimization of performance. This: a life ordered around what is true and lasting. Let that be what you're building toward." },
    { v:"Search me, O God, and know my heart; test me and know my anxious thoughts.", r:"Psalm 139:23", d:"Come in, see everything, know all of it. The prayer of complete openness — no hiding, no performance. God's searching is not condemnation. It is the attentive care of someone who wants to heal what is hurt and redirect what has drifted. Let him search. Trust what he finds." },
    { v:"Point out anything in me that offends you, and lead me along the path of everlasting life.", r:"Psalm 139:24", d:"Lead me along the path of everlasting life — ask God to lead you on it in your training, in your rest, in how you speak about your body. The path is already laid. You just need to stay on it, one faithful day at a time." },
    { v:"How precious are your thoughts about me, O God. They cannot be numbered!", r:"Psalm 139:17", d:"He is thinking about you right now — too many thoughts to count. Every day of the year: individually attended to, individually held in the thoughts of a God whose attention never runs out. You were thought about today. And yesterday. And every ordinary day in between." },
    { v:"I can never escape from your Spirit! I can never get away from your presence!", r:"Psalm 139:7", d:"You cannot go where God is not. The sessions where you felt alone — he was there. The seasons where faith was hard — he was there. The dark mornings and discouraging weeks — he was there. You could not get away from his presence even when you felt farthest from him." },
    { v:"You go before me and follow me. You place your hand of blessing on my head.", r:"Psalm 139:5", d:"Before and behind. The coming year — God is already there. The year behind — God was in all of it. And his hand of blessing is on your head right now. You are going into the future preceded and followed by God, with his hand on you in the present." },
    { v:"Such knowledge is too wonderful for me, too great for me to understand!", r:"Psalm 139:6", d:"Too wonderful to understand. The extent of God's knowledge of you, his attention to you, his presence with you — it surpasses comprehension. You cannot think your way to the full depth of it. You can only receive it. Let it be too wonderful. Worship the God who exceeds your understanding." },
    { v:"For his unfailing love toward those who fear him is as great as the height of the heavens above the earth.", r:"Psalm 103:11", d:"As great as the height of the heavens — this is not a modest claim. The scale of God's love is cosmically proportioned. The love that has sustained you — through the hard seasons and the good ones — is as vast as the universe itself. Let that settle in." },
    { v:"He has removed our sins as far from us as the east is from the west.", r:"Psalm 103:12", d:"He has removed your sins as far as the east is from the west — an unbounded distance with no meeting point. The regrets of this year — the missed sessions, the poor choices, the ways you fell short — God has removed them. Not shelved them. Removed them. Begin what comes next from cleared ground." },
    { v:"The Lord is like a father to his children, tender and compassionate to those who fear him.", r:"Psalm 103:13", d:"Tender and compassionate — the Father who watches your year is not keeping a grudging tally of your failures. He is tender — moved by what moves you, attentive to what hurts you. Compassionate — motivated by mercy, not obligation. You are tended by a Father who loves you this way." },
    { v:"For he knows how weak we are; he remembers we are only dust.", r:"Psalm 103:14", d:"He knows how weak you are. He remembers you are dust. The expectations God has for you account for your humanity. He is not surprised by your limitations. He made them. He loves you inside them. Let that settle the performance anxiety." },
    { v:"But the love of the Lord remains forever with those who fear him.", r:"Psalm 103:17", d:"His love remains forever — not just through the good seasons. Forever. Including the seasons you're not proud of, the years that were harder than expected. The love remains. This is the constant: the love of the Lord does not change." },
    { v:"Praise the Lord, I tell myself, and never forget the good things he does for me.", r:"Psalm 103:2", d:"Never forget. Year-end is the perfect time for intentional remembering. The good things God did for you — count them. Write them down. Speak them out loud. Let the record of his faithfulness become the foundation for your confidence about what comes next." },
    { v:"May the God of hope fill you completely with joy and peace because you trust in him. Then you will overflow with confident hope.", r:"Romans 15:13", d:"Overflow — the hope that comes from trusting God is not just enough for you, it spills over. The joy and peace that fill you become the environment you create around you. Ask to be filled completely — so that what overflows reaches the people who need it most." },
    { v:"Now may our Lord Jesus Christ himself and God our Father comfort you and strengthen you in every good thing you do and say.", r:"2 Thessalonians 2:16–17", d:"Comfort and strengthen — both, together. Comfort comes first — loved, held in grace. From that place, strength grows. Rest in the comfort. The strength will follow." },
    { v:"For a child is born to us, a son is given to us. And he will be called: Wonderful Counselor, Mighty God, Everlasting Father, Prince of Peace.", r:"Isaiah 9:6", d:"Wonderful Counselor. Mighty God. Everlasting Father. Prince of Peace. Four names for the One who came and who still walks with you. He is wise enough to counsel your confusion. Mighty enough to sustain you. Fatherly enough to hold your brokenness. Peaceful enough to quiet the anxiety." },
    { v:"Glory to God in highest heaven, and peace on earth to those with whom God is pleased.", r:"Luke 2:14", d:"Peace on earth — not peace as the absence of conflict, but peace as shalom: wholeness, flourishing, everything in its right place. This is what God is working toward in you. The glory goes upward. The peace comes down. Receive it." },
    { v:"For this is how God loved the world: He gave his one and only Son, so that everyone who believes in him will not perish but have eternal life.", r:"John 3:16", d:"Loved us and gave us eternal comfort and wonderful hope. The comfort is eternal — not temporary. The hope is wonderful — not ordinary. You are comforted. You are holding a wonderful hope. Walk into what comes next carrying both." },
    { v:"The night is almost gone; the day of salvation will soon be here. So remove your dark deeds like dirty clothes, and put on the shining armor of right living.", r:"Romans 13:12", d:"He gave — the love of God is not theoretical or sentimental. It is acted. He gave the most costly thing he had. For you — not for the idealized version, but for you as you actually are. The year ending, with all its imperfection and all its grace, is the year in which God loved you this completely. Receive it." },
    { v:"I remain confident of this: I will see the goodness of the Lord in the land of the living.", r:"Psalm 27:13", d:"Light for the path. As one year closes and another opens, the same promise holds: you don't need to see the whole road. You need enough light for the next step. Walk in the light you have. The next step will be lit when you get there." },
    { v:"This means that anyone who belongs to Christ has become a new person. The old life is gone; a new life has begun!", r:"2 Corinthians 5:17", d:"Search me — the prayer that begins the new year well. Come in, see everything, know the anxious thoughts and the hidden things. Not to condemn what you find, but to begin the work of healing and renewal from the inside out." },
    { v:"Surely your goodness and unfailing love will pursue me all the days of my life, and I will live in the house of the Lord forever.", r:"Psalm 23:6", d:"Goodness and unfailing love pursuing you all the days of your life — not just waiting for you when you turn around. Pursuing. Actively. Chasing. You cannot out-run the goodness and love of God. They will catch you. Let them." },
    { v:"And I am certain that God, who began a good work within you, will continue his work until it is finally finished.", r:"Philippians 1:6", d:"He who began a good work in you will carry it on to completion. The year is ending. The work is not. God does not finish projects partially. He is not abandoning the work of forming you into who you're becoming. The work continues into the new year, sustained by the One who began it." },
  ],
};

function getTodayScripture() {
  const now = new Date();
  const month = now.getMonth() + 1;
  const day = now.getDate();
  const mm = String(month).padStart(2,"0");
  const dd = String(day).padStart(2,"0");

  // Special dates first
  if (SPECIAL[`${mm}-${dd}`]) return { ...SPECIAL[`${mm}-${dd}`], isSpecial: true };

  // Liturgical season overrides
  const season = getLiturgicalSeason(now);
  if (SEASONS[season]) return { ...SEASONS[season], isSpecial: true };

  // Pick from monthly array by day
  const arr = BY_MONTH[month] || BY_MONTH[1];
  const entry = arr[(day - 1) % arr.length];
  return { v: entry.v, r: entry.r, d: entry.d || null, season: null, isSunday: now.getDay() === 0 };
}

// ── Sunday reflection prompts ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
const SUNDAY_PROMPTS = [
  "What is one thing your body did this week that you are grateful for?",
  "Where did you feel God's strength most clearly in your training this week?",
  "What would it look like to honor God with your body more fully this coming week?",
  "What is one area of your health you want to bring to God in prayer today?",
  "Where did you hold back this week — in training, in rest, or in trusting God?",
  "What did this week's effort reveal about your character? What do you want to build on?",
  "How can the strength you are building serve the people around you this week?",
  "What do you need to release — a comparison, a shame, a fear — before the new week begins?",
];

function getSundayPrompt() {
  const week = Math.floor(new Date().getDate() / 7);
  return SUNDAY_PROMPTS[week % SUNDAY_PROMPTS.length];
}

// ── Cross SVG ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
function CrossMark({ color = "#555" }) {
  return (
    <svg width="13" height="15" viewBox="0 0 13 15" fill="none" style={{ flexShrink: 0, marginTop: "2px" }}>
      <rect x="5.5" y="0" width="2" height="15" rx="1" fill={color} />
      <rect x="0" y="5" width="13" height="2" rx="1" fill={color} />
    </svg>
  );
}

// ── Component ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
export default function DailyScripture({ accent = "#2563a8", inHeader = false }) {
  const today = new Date().toISOString().slice(0, 10);
  const notesKey = `scripture_notes_${today}`;
  const [expanded, setExpanded] = useState(false);
  const [notes, setNotes] = useState(() => {
    try { return localStorage.getItem(notesKey) || ""; } catch { return ""; }
  });

  const scripture = getTodayScripture();
  const isSunday = new Date().getDay() === 0;
  const sundayPrompt = isSunday ? getSundayPrompt() : null;

  function handleNotes(e) {
    setNotes(e.target.value);
    try { localStorage.setItem(notesKey, e.target.value); } catch {}
  }

  if (!scripture) return null;

  const seasonLabel = scripture.season || (isSunday ? "Sunday · Rest & Reflection" : "Today's Word");

  return (
    <div style={{
      ...(inHeader
        ? { margin: "0 0 12px 0", borderRadius: "6px", overflow: "hidden", border: "1px solid #2a2a2a", background: "#1a1a1a" }
        : { margin: "10px 14px", borderRadius: "10px", overflow: "hidden", border: "1px solid #222", background: "#111" }
      ),
      ...F,
    }}>

      {/* Always-visible header — tap to expand */}
      <button onClick={() => setExpanded(p => !p)} style={{
        width: "100%", background: "none", border: "none", cursor: "pointer",
        padding: inHeader ? "10px 12px" : "13px 15px",
        display: "flex", alignItems: "flex-start", gap: "10px", textAlign: "left", ...F,
      }}>
        <CrossMark color={accent} />
        <div style={{ flex: 1, minWidth: 0 }}>
          <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.22em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: accent, marginBottom: "5px" }}>
            {seasonLabel}
          </div>
          {/* Full verse always shown */}
          <div style={{ fontSize: "13px", color: "#e8e0cc", lineHeight: "1.7", fontStyle: "italic" }}>
            "{scripture.v}"
          </div>
          {/* Reference always shown */}
          <div style={{ fontSize: "10px", color: accent, marginTop: "6px", letterSpacing: "0.06em" }}>
            — {scripture.r}
          </div>
        </div>
        <span style={{ color: "#444", fontSize: "10px", flexShrink: 0, paddingTop: "2px" }}>
          {expanded ? "▲" : "▼"}
        </span>
      </button>

      {/* Expanded section — reflection + notes */}
      {expanded && (
        <div style={{ borderTop: "1px solid #1e1e1e" }}>

          {/* Reflection */}
          {scripture.d && (
            <div style={{ padding: "14px 15px 12px" }}>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.18em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#555", marginBottom: "9px" }}>
                Reflection
              </div>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "13px", color: "#b8b0a0", lineHeight: "1.85" }}>
                {scripture.d}
              </div>
            </div>
          )}

          {/* Sunday prompt */}
          {isSunday && sundayPrompt && (
            <div style={{ padding: "10px 15px 12px", borderTop: "1px solid #1e1e1e" }}>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.18em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#555", marginBottom: "9px" }}>
                This week
              </div>
              <div style={{ fontSize: "13px", color: "#b8b0a0", lineHeight: "1.8", fontStyle: "italic" }}>
                {sundayPrompt}
              </div>
            </div>
          )}

          {/* Personal notes */}
          <div style={{ padding: "10px 15px 14px", borderTop: "1px solid #1e1e1e" }}>
            <div style={{ fontSize: "8px", letterSpacing: "0.18em", textTransform: "uppercase", color: "#444", marginBottom: "7px" }}>
              Your notes
            </div>
            <textarea
              value={notes}
              onChange={handleNotes}
              placeholder="Add your own reflection..."
              style={{
                width: "100%", boxSizing: "border-box",
                background: "#1a1a1a", border: "1px solid #2a2a2a",
                borderRadius: "5px", color: "#c8c0b0", fontSize: "12px",
                lineHeight: "1.65", padding: "8px 10px", resize: "none",
                outline: "none", minHeight: "70px", ...F,
              }}
              rows={3}
            />
          </div>

        </div>
      )}
    </div>
  );
}
